# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: galley
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] The **Cagayan battles** (*Combates de Cagayán* in Spanish, カガヤンの戦い *Kagayan no Tatakai* in Japanese) occurred in 1582 between amphibious forces of the Spanish Philippines, led by Juan Pablo de Carrión, and Japanese wokou pirates, led by Tay Fusa, possibly identified with Naya Sukezaemon.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] The pirates had build a settlement near the Cagayan river, which the Spanish were ordered to assault.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] Although severely outnumbered, the Spanish defeated the wokou and forced them to abandon the island.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] Carrión later built the city of Nueva Segovia, now Lal-lo, in one of the placements of the battle.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] The battles became a source of controversy in popular culture after they became known in the 21st century.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] They are usually described as a clash between Japanese samurai and Spanish tercio soldiers, two highly regarded fighting forces, despite in reality it featured neither samurai nor tercios.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] It was the second time the Spanish clashed against Japanese, the first being the 1574 Battle of Manila, where a large Sino-Japanese wokou army was defeated.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] As in the first, the Spanish prevailed thanks to superior weaponry and training.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] By 1573, the commercial routes of the Manila galleon attracted piratic activity to the island of Luzón, the core of the Spanish Philippines.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] Japanese raiders had frequented the northern lands of the island before the Spanish conquest of the territory.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] The Spanish had already faced a large-scale wokou invasion in 1574, when the pirate Limahong besieged Manila in 1574 with a huge army containing both Chinese and Japanese before being repulsed from the city.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] Despite this, wokou sometimes alternated between trade and piracy depending on their needs.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] Japanese traders were welcomed in Manila, while Spanish merchants in turn commerced in Japan.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] In 1581, the authorities in Manila were informed that Japanese pirates had built a settlement near Aparri, Cagayan, in the northern land of the island.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] They Japanese used this port, called *Puerto de Japón* by the Spaniards, to trade weapons for gold and raid the nearby natives.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] The following year, Spanish governor Gonzalo Ronquillo de Peñalosa ordered Captain Juan Pablo de Carrión to search and destroy it.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] The Wokou fleet based off Puerto de Japón was reportedly composed of 18 junks.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] According to Japanese sources, the port itself was defended by 600 fighters.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] The Spanish were able to distinguish the Japanese from the Chinese and clearly identified those, although wokou were nonetheless composed by a motley mix of Asian ethnicities and even European outcasts.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] They were armed with western artillery, arquebuses and steel armor bought from the Portuguese, as well as probably Japanese-made Tanegashima guns.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] Spanish sources also describe them as wielding two-handed sabers like broadswords, probably *nodachi* or *nagamaki*.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] They were led by "Tay Fusa", which does not correspond to a Japanese name but could be a transliteration of *Taifu-san* or *Taifu-sama*, with *taifu* (大夫) being a word for a Japanese medieval chieftain rank.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] Authors identified him with Naya Sukezaemon, who later became a Japanese merchant in Luzón.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] The 70-year-old Carrión had a long career in battles against hostile natives.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] He gathered a fleet formed by the galley *Capitana*, the carrack *San Yusepe* and five frigates brought from Vigan.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] He embarked 40 soldiers, most of them Hispanic criollos, mestizos and Tlaxcaltec natives, with experience in the Chichimeca Wars and the very conquest of the Philippines.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] Only a handful of them would have fought in the wars of Europe.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] All of them, however, were well trained in the regular tactics of the tercios.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] After capturing an unrelated Chinese corsair junk, the Hispanic flotilla passed the Cape Bojeador.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] They encountered a heavy wokou junk near the coast, whose crew had recently ravaged a native village.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] Carrión destroyed its main mast with his artillery and boarded the ship with the *Capitana*, but the junk turned out to contain 200 fighters armed with courasses and pikes, enough to repulse the boarding party and board their own galley.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] Other 60 Japanese arquebusiers stayed in the junk shooting at the Spanish.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] The galley's deck became a battlefield, but the Spanish improvised a parapet and managed to improbably rout the Japanese from the aftercastle, inflicting heavy casualties with their own arquebusiers and pikemen.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] Watching the rest of the Spanish fleet pirates returned to the junk and tried to escape, but the *San Yusepe* blocked their way and ravaged the junk with its broadside artillery.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] Several Japanese jumped overboard and tried to swam away, drowning due to the weight of their armor.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] At the end, only 18 Japanese remained alive to surrender.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] The Spanish had suffered their first casualties, among them the galley's captain Pedro Lucas, and the *Capitana* was damaged and taking water.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] The flotilla continued up to the Cagayán River, which Carrión explored with the *Capitana*.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] Within the river, Carrión sighted eighteen skiff-sized sampans sacking a coastal village.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] The sampans attacked him, but he routed them, killing 200 pirates and supposedly a son of Tay Fusa.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] He then sighted Puerto de Japón, defended by 600-1,000 fighters and much artillery.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] The *San Yusepe* could not follow Carrión with the rest of the flotilla, as its captain, Luis Callejo, ordered to turn back upon a false alarm, after which the carrack hit a shallow and broke its anchors.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] Meanwhile, Carrión ordered to disembark, erect fortifications and arm them with the flotilla's artillery.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] Tay Fusa sent messengers to try to negotiate, stating that the Spanish "were robbers like himself, but that he was there first, and had come at his king's command".
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] He proposed he would leave the island if Carrión paid him a large sum in gold to compensate the losses they would suffer, but the Spanish refused.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] According to Keiji Igawa, Carrión answered he was there to protect the natives and recover the gold Tay Fusa had sacked, and threatened to bring 600 men against him, warning the pirate that his own men would kill him if he did not accept.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] Intimidated, Tay Fusa would have ordered to withdraw from the island without a fight.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] Seiichi Iwao and the Spanish sources instead state that Tay Fusa ordered to attack and a battle took place.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] The wokou tried to storm the fortifications with a force of some 600 strong.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] The Spanish beat them back thrice, capitalizing on the safety of their earthworks to fire volleys of arquebuses and artillery at the oncoming waves of men.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] Some of the Japanese reached the trenches, only to be contained by the Spanish pikemen.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] The Spanish knew the Japanese would try to seize the pikes even if wounded by them, so Carrión had ordered to grease the upper half of the shafts.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] The Japanese launched a new attack after a rest, suffering new casualties to the Spanish gunfire.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] A third assault from the flank was also broken by artillery.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] By this point, the Spanish started running out of gunpowder due to the sheer number of enemies.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] Carrión was forced to order a defense by forming pike squares and placing rodeleros to attack from underneath.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] The Japanese attacked again and clashed against the greased pikes, but finding little space to comfortably use katanas and other two-handed weapons, they were decimated by the rodeleros.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] Finally, the pirate army routed, abandoning their position and withdrawing towards the sea, leaving behind their dead and wounded.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] Casualties in the Japanese side were 200, according to sources, or up to 800 in other Spanish sources.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] In comparison, Spanish casualties were said to be not higher than 20.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] With the region pacified and the arrival of reinforcements, Carrión founded the city of Nueva Segovia (now Lal-lo).
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] With their defeat, wokou activity disappeared from Cagayan, leading most pirates to relocate in Lingayen.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] Piracy, and the impression left by the fierceness of the battle, continued being felt in Manila, leading the Spanish authorities to request more troops and for the city to be fortified in order not to disrupt commerce with China.
[src:galley/1582-cagayan-battles] For their part, commerce with the Japanese continued in the Philippines, remaining largely private enterprises before the establishment of the *shuinsen* system.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] The **Proclamation for Suppressing of Pirates** (also known simply as the **Act of Grace**, though not an Act of Parliament) was a royal proclamation issued by George I of Great Britain on 5 September 1717.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] It promised a pardon for acts of piracy committed before the following 5 January, to those pirates who surrendered themselves to the correct authority before a deadline.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Originally, the surrender had to occur on or before 5 September 1718; this was later extended by a second proclamation to 1 July 1719.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] The proclamation also included bounties for the capture of pirates who failed to surrender before the deadline, as well as offering rewards for pirate crew members who facilitated the capture of their captains.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] In December 1718, a further extension of the deadline was suggested, in hopes of dissuading pirates from entering Spanish service during the War of the Quadruple Alliance.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Kings James I, James II and William III issued similar pardons or proclamations in the prior century.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] With the end of the first Anglo-Spanish war under James I, and the corresponding end to English privateering in 1603, English sailors resorted to piracy.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] In 1611, Captain Richard Bishop became one of the first notable pirates to be pardoned, having surrendered partly due to qualms about attacking English ships.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] In 1611, the English government was willing to offer a general pardon to pirates, on condition that they surrender their ships and goods.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] The following year, the privy council of James I offered a general pardon without this condition.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] At least 12 pirate crews surrendered to the general pardon, though a large portion of Baughe's crew would shortly return to piracy.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Captain Roger Middleton, who sailed first to Ireland then to Mehdya to deliver the pardon, extracted bribes from pirates in exchange for their pardon.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] The lack of competing pirates in Ireland due to the general pardon saw Henry Mainwaring become notorious in 1613 as leader of a pirate fleet.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] He would receive offers from Tuscany, Savoy, Tunis and Spain of a pardon should he surrender; however, consistent with his not attacking English ships, in June 1616 he instead accepted an English offer of pardon, having sought one since the previous year (as too had Lording Barry).
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Clive Senior suggests that the government had an incentive to pardon pirates, since this would keep these potentially useful seamen available in case of war.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Around the 1670s, an expedition to suppress piracy in the Spanish West Indies using pardons was planned, but never went ahead.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] On 22 May 1687, James II renewed the proclamation for the suppression of pirates, offering a limited time in which any pirate who surrendered would receive a pardon.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] That August, he commissioned Sir Robert Holmes to suppress piracy in a squadron sent to the West Indies.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] On 20 January 1688, James II issued a proclamation (offering pardons to pirates who surrendered to Holmes or to an appointee of his) in order to ensure that colonial governors would cooperate with Holmes and his agents.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Holmes' fleet achieved a temporary reduction in piracy, but the number of pirates had increased again by 1693.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] On 8 December 1698, William III issued a proclamation offering pardons to pirates east of the Cape of Good Hope who surrendered to Captain Thomas Warren.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Henry Every and William Kidd were specifically exempted from receiving this pardon.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] By the time that Warren arrived in Madagascar, the Act of Grace had expired.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] By promising to extend the deadline for surrender, Warren obtained the surrender of Robert Culliford, among others; however, these pirates were taken to trial and all except Culliford were hanged.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] The fact that pirates such as Joseph Bradish and those in Kidd's company were not offered amnesty by the authorities contributed to scepticism regarding acts of grace, including among the crew of Bartholomew Roberts more than two decades later.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] With armistices in 1712, followed by the Peace of Utrecht in 1713, the state of war (which had existed since 1702 as part of the War of the Spanish Succession) between England/Great Britain on one side and France and Spain on the other came to an end.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Employment for sailors became difficult to find and poorly paid, as privateering commissions became useless and as the Royal Navy discharged over 36,000 men (nearly three-quarters of those it had employed).
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] In spite of the peace, Spanish *guarda costa* continued to seize English ships (based on their possession of Spanish coin), harming and imprisoning English sailors, as well as discouraging the merchant shipping which would otherwise have offered legitimate employment.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] This led some sailors to resort to piracy.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] In 1715, a Royal Navy anti-piracy campaign began in earnest.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] No pirate ships were captured till 1717, the year that HMS *Scarborough* caused the destruction of a pirate galley and a sloop near Saint Croix, but failed to capture the crew.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] At this time, some 20–30 pirate vessels remained at sea.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] The reasons for the campaign's ineffectiveness till 1718 included the vastness of the seas in which pirates operated, pirates' better knowledge of those seas, outdated intelligence, and a desire to cut costs (which resulted in a lack of ships, maintenance and seamen).
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] The campaign's initial lack of success saw the British government resort to offering pardons to pirates by issuing the proclamation of 1717.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] For several months, piracy in the West Indies – particularly around Jamaica – had been such a problem for the merchants and masters of ships of Bristol that they petitioned the king for its suppression.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Following receipt of this petition, in May 1717, Secretary of State Joseph Addison asked the Council of Trade and Plantations to recommend to the king how best to achieve this.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Having consulted merchants and other interested parties, the council agreed that the issue was urgent, replying that "the whole trade from Great Britain to those parts" was "in imminent danger of being lost".
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] The council heard that piracy even reached the seas near the northern continent, and that at least one fourth-rate or two fifth-rates were required to suppress it.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] In addition, the consultees proposed a royal pardon for pirates who surrendered themselves; the council hoped that this would reform the pirates into law-abiding subjects.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Finally, the council recommended that the Bahamas be settled and fortified to prevent pirates from sheltering there.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Meanwhile, in Virginia, Lieutenant-Governor Alexander Spotswood recommended reducing the number of pirates either by force (to serve as a deterrent), or by offering a pardon to those who would submit – although he doubted that all the pirates would accept such an offer.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] In August 1717, soon-to-be Governor of Jamaica Nicholas Lawes advocated both royal clemency and an increased presence of warships to reduce the number of pirates and protect Jamaican trade.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] The pirates themselves threatened to attack Bermuda and (according to Lieutenant-Governor Bennett) "make a new Madagascar of it" if they were not offered a pardon, communicating this through the masters of captured ships.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Following a justification for the proclamation, the text defines who it is pirates may surrender to and by what date.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] The proclamation also defined the following bounties for the capture of pirates who failed to surrender before the deadline.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] It further offered the following rewards for pirate crew members facilitating the capture of their captains.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] On 9 December, the council also recommended a further extension of the date, hoping to dissuade pirates from entering Spanish service during the War of the Quadruple Alliance.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] No pirate who surrendered before the deadline was excepted from the promise of a pardon.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Furthermore, by late February 1718, it was decided that governors would require a commission under the Great Seal in order to grant royal pardons as promised by the proclamation.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Such commissions were ordered and prepared that July; in addition, governors were then permitted to pardon acts of piracy which occurred before 23 July 1718 (as opposed to the original date of 5 January 1718).
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Governor Spotswood and Governor Rogers received commissions for which this date was 18 August.) In the days following the 1718 proclamation, updated commissions were once again ordered and sent.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] When news of the proclamation reached Bermuda, Lieutenant-Governor Benjamin Bennett sent his son in December 1717 to the Republic of Pirates on New Providence.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] The arrival of Bennett's son with copies of the proclamation caused the pirates there to divide into two factions, depending on whether they planned to accept the pardon.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] The faction rejecting the pardon included Jacobites, and was led by Charles Vane.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Those rejecting the pardon supported fortifying the island, as did those wishing to secure their plunder, but when a general council was called, no action was agreed on.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] While the Jacobites sought support from George Camocke, other pirates sailed to nearby British colonies to receive a pardon, including Henry Jennings and around 150 others who sailed to Bermuda, most of whom would return to piracy.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] The likes of Christopher Condent, Christopher Winter and Nicholas Brown fled New Providence, with Winter and Brown sailing to Spanish Cuba.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] On 23 February 1718, Captain Vincent Pearse arrived at Nassau, having sailed from New York on HMS *Phoenix*.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Pearse's crew was informed of how to find Vane by pirates intending to accept the pardon.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Although Vane's crew was apprehended and his sloop, the *Lark*, taken, pirates Hornigold, Leslie, Burgess and Nichols persuaded Pearse to release Vane and his crew as a show of good faith.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Though Pearse lacked the authority to issue pardons, he offered signed certificates to pirates who would surrender to him.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] 209 accepted this offer, less than half of the pirates on New Providence.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Having already returned to piracy and attacked the crew of the *Phoenix*, on 4 April, Vane left New Providence on the recaptured *Lark*.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Pearse and the *Phoenix* left four days later.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Vane would return in late April, and again in July.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] On 24 July 1718, the new Governor of the Bahamas, Woodes Rogers, arrived off Hog Island (near Nassau), along with a series of vessels which included three Royal Navy warships.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] The following day, Vane left New Providence and escaped this force with Charles Yeats on Yeats' ship *Katherine*.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] When he set foot on New Providence on 27 July, Rogers was welcomed by pro-pardon pirates, including Thomas Walker, Hornigold, and Hornigold's and Josiah Burgess's crews.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] (Burgess and Hornigold had already been pardoned by this time.) On 1 August, Rogers' new council granted the King's Pardon to some 200 pirates.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Edward England, having been among those rejecting the pardon, sailed to Africa after this.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Following its departure on 10 September, the crew of the *Buck* (a sloop-of-war taken to New Providence by Rogers, now with reformed pirates among its crew) turned pirate.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] The *Buck*'s new pirate crew included reformed pirates Thomas Anstis and Howell Davis, as well as a man who had come from England aboard the *Buck*, Walter Kennedy.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Moreover, Rogers estimated that 150 pirates had left New Providence between the end of July and late October, including pirates hoping to join Vane.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Indeed, that October saw the departure of three sloops, which two days later experienced a mutiny led by pardoned pirates John Auger, Phineas Bunce and Dennis McCarthy.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Due to the threat from both committed pirates and the Spanish (particularly after news of the War of the Quadruple Alliance arrived in March 1719), Rogers employed pardoned ex-pirates as pirate hunters and privateers.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] These included Hornigold, John Cockram and Burgess.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] By the end of November 1718, the pirate hunters had captured more than 10 prisoners, including Nicholas Woodall.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Eight such previously pardoned prisoners, including Auger and McCarthy, would be hanged that December.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Rogers received a commission to pardon in January 1719.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] That month, he wrote of his doubts that most remaining pirates would surrender, stating that reducing their numbers would be difficult without a greater presence of naval vessels under a governor's control.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Governor Bennett was optimistic about the pardon, reporting that he had been giving certificates to pirates who surrendered, and requesting instructions regarding how to ensure surrendered pirates would receive their pardon.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] The need for such instructions became more pressing as pirates became impatient to leave Bermuda.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] The following March, Bennett reported that there were pirates who refused to take the pardon without assurance that they would be allowed to keep their plunder.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] From March to July, Bennett's worsening predicament was repeatedly relayed to Secretary of State James Craggs by the Council of Trade and Plantations, which also blamed the fact that surrendered pirates were returning to piracy on governors' lack of any power to pardon without a commission.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Bennett would receive this commission by the following October.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Around April 1718, Henry Jennings took a privateering commission from Bennett to hunt Charles Vane.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] A year later, shortly after news of the War of the Quadruple Alliance arrived in New Providence, pirates from the Bahamas surrendered to Bennett in April 1719 and received the king's pardon.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] That May, more pirates surrendered on condition that they be allowed to keep their plunder.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Bennett reported that the pardon was working, since he was now only aware of ongoing piracy by Christopher Condent and Edward England.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Blackbeard heard of the proclamation around 5 December 1717, from the captain of a sloop which he had attacked.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Around early May 1718, on New Providence, about 300 of his roughly 700 men left his company, some intending to take the King's Pardon.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] During his blockade of Charles Town around the end of that month, Blackbeard rejected a pardon from Governor Robert Johnson.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Around early June, near Beaufort, North Carolina, Blackbeard allowed Stede Bonnet to sail to Bath, North Carolina, to be pardoned by Governor Charles Eden.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] With Bonnet away, Blackbeard and about 100 others took the entire company's plunder – including Bonnet's share – and sailed to Bath along a different route, where they too received the King's Pardon.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Blackbeard and Bonnet would each return to piracy, Blackbeard using the veneer of legality afforded to him by Eden and his pardon, and Bonnet attempting to conceal his identity.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Bonnet would later be executed, and Blackbeard would be killed while fighting Virginia authorities.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Quartermaster William Howard, already convicted and sentenced, was pardoned after he was made aware that the deadline for surrendering had been extended, while Israel Hands (who had also been convicted) was pardoned, apparently for testifying against corrupt North Carolina officials.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] During Charles Vane's blockade of Charles Town around 30 August 1718, Charles Yeats defected from Vane's command and, with a cargo of Guinean slaves, surrendered to Governor Johnson in exchange for a pardon.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] From February to March 1718, Commander in Chief of Jamaica Peter Heywood reported that a considerable number of pirates had surrendered, including Hornigold.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] However, that August, the council and assembly reported that the pirates were numerous in spite of the proclamation.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Governor Nicholas Lawes' commission to pardon arrived by the following October.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] When the proclamation of 1718 was read and news of the War of the Quadruple Alliance arrived in March 1719, Governor Lawes wrote of his expectation that more pirates would surrender, the pirates having "long wish[ed] for" such a war.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] He also remarked that more pirates would have surrendered beforehand had they not been supplied with necessities and information from people on shore.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Henry Jennings and Leigh Ashworth became privateers based in Jamaica.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Ashworth resumed his piracy in May 1719.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Governors Robert Hunter (of New York) and Samuel Shute (of Massachusetts and New Hampshire) each wrote of the proclamation's ineffectiveness in June 1718.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] In Virginia, due to fears that former pirates would return to piracy, a proclamation was issued that July to restrict their carrying arms or assembling in large numbers.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] Commissions to pardon pirates arrived in New England by that September, in Barbados by October, in the Leeward Islands by November, in Virginia by December 1718, and in Nova Scotia by March 1719.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] In December 1718, Secretary of State James Craggs warned governors against illegally receiving bribes in exchange for accepting pirates' surrender.
[src:galley/1717-1718-acts-of-grace] As the Caribbean became less hospitable to pirates, Africa became the destination of Olivier Levasseur, Edward England and Paulsgrave Williams.
[src:galley/1985-lahad-datu-ambush] The **1985 Lahad Datu ambush** was a series of robberies and random shootings that occurred on 23 September 1985 when 15–20 armed foreign pirates landed on the coast of Lahad Datu, Malaysia, and stormed the town.
[src:galley/1985-lahad-datu-ambush] The pirates shot at random targets, killing at least 21 people and injuring 11 others, and stole some $200,000 from a local bank as well as another $5,000 from the Malaysia Airlines office.
[src:galley/1985-lahad-datu-ambush] Most areas in the east coast of Sabah are known for many Filipino communities, both legal and illegal.
[src:galley/1985-lahad-datu-ambush] These areas have become a haven for pirates from the Philippines and Sabah itself has suffered 10 major attacks since 1976.
[src:galley/1985-lahad-datu-ambush] On the evening of 23 September, a number of armed men clad in jungle green uniforms appeared in the town and started to shoot random targets.
[src:galley/1985-lahad-datu-ambush] The shoot-out left the town with significant destruction and blood could be found everywhere.
[src:galley/1985-lahad-datu-ambush] One of the victims, a pregnant woman, was shot while being driven home in a van.
[src:galley/1985-lahad-datu-ambush] The van driver brought her to the hospital but she was pronounced dead on arrival.
[src:galley/1985-lahad-datu-ambush] Another victim, a Chinese man, was injured by a gunshot during the raid.
[src:galley/1985-lahad-datu-ambush] The instability of the Philippines has caused major economic problems for Sabah.
[src:galley/1985-lahad-datu-ambush] Philippine army raids against anti-Ferdinand Marcos factions in the Sulu and Mindanao islands have left many houses and fields destroyed, forcing an estimated 100,000 Moro people in the Southern Philippines to flee to Sabah.
[src:galley/1985-lahad-datu-ambush] While many who have not left the Philippine islands have involved themselves in criminal activities, mainly on smuggling and armed robbery.
[src:galley/1985-lahad-datu-ambush] After their successful attack, the pirates later retreated to a jetty where they engaged a group of Malaysian Marine Police.
[src:galley/1985-lahad-datu-ambush] Two of the pirates were wounded during a shootout with the marine police, but still managed to carry their injured allies into two awaiting pump boats and made their getaway back to the Philippines.
[src:galley/1985-lahad-datu-ambush] The following day, the Marine Police launched surprise attacks on an island which was believed to be their hide-out and managed to kill five pirates.
[src:galley/1985-lahad-datu-ambush] While the rest of the pirates escaped to the international border, the police recovered a number of M16 rifles and a whole armoury of assorted weapons.
[src:galley/1985-lahad-datu-ambush] An unverified report alleged that in their retaliation, the Royal Malaysian Navy brought four ships and three helicopters to attack a Filipino island, bombing the island's settlement, burning houses down and killing 53 Filipino residents.
[src:galley/1985-lahad-datu-ambush] The Malaysian Embassy in Manila declined to comment on the report and said that the Malaysian embassy had not received any information from the Philippine government or from the Malaysia's capital of Kuala Lumpur.
[src:galley/2022-in-piracy] The COVID-19 pandemic continued to impact maritime piracy in 2022.
[src:galley/2022-in-piracy] The *Rwabee* hijacking and hostage-taking in January had incentivized a return to coordinated naval anti-piracy measures on the Aden coast and in the Red Sea.
[src:galley/2022-in-piracy] In 2024, research would indicate that the United Nations Security Council resolution for foreign navies to patrol Somali territorial waters had lapsed, in March, 2022, with the need for it to continue being then unperceived.
[src:galley/2022-in-piracy] Piracy and armed robbery in the Singapore Strait accounted for 65% of piracy incidents in Asia in 2022, according to the Regional Cooperation Agreement on Combating Piracy and Armed Robbery against Ships in Asia (ReCaap).
[src:galley/2022-in-piracy] The Caribbean was also among the most affected areas.
[src:galley/2022-in-piracy] The Strait saw an increase in piracy, accounting for close to 30% of incidents, as did Asia's, Celebs and Sulu Seas, Manila anchorages, and in the disputed waters of the eastern Sabah coast in Asia.
[src:galley/2022-in-piracy] Efforts to reduce piracy off the coast of Somalia appeared to have succeeded, with no ship hijackings for ransom since March 2017.
[src:galley/2022-in-piracy] Globally, incidents of piracy and armed robbery at anchor or at sea were at their lowest levels since 1992, with the vast majority of events occurring at night, under cover of darkness.
[src:galley/2022-in-piracy] The United Nations published *The situation with respect to piracy and armed robbery at sea off the coast of Somalia* in November.
[src:galley/2022-in-piracy] India enacted its first domestic anti-piracy legislation as the Maritime Anti-Piracy Act 2022, criminalizing maritime piracy and empowering Indian agencies with the authority to respond to threats.
[src:galley/2022-in-piracy] Sea piracy by cyberattack using ransomware had also become a growing threat to shipping companies.
[src:galley/2022-in-piracy] Pirate attacks of 2022 include events listed below; the list is not exhaustive.
[src:galley/2022-in-piracy] On January 3, MV *Rwabee* was hijacked by Houthis in the Red Sea.
[src:galley/2022-in-piracy] The UAE-flagged cargo ship was said to be transporting civilian medical supplies.
[src:galley/2022-in-piracy] Hostages, including 11 crew, were released in April.
[src:galley/2022-in-piracy] During August 29–30, a support ship from Iran's Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps Navy (IRGCN) attempted to capture a U.S.
[src:galley/2022-in-piracy] Navy unmanned surface vessel in the Persian Gulf.
[src:galley/2022-in-piracy] *Shahid Baziar* continued towing the Saildrone Explorer for about four hours before releasing it, while being shadowed and radioed by the *USS Thunderbolt*.
[src:galley/2023-in-piracy] A resurgence of piracy off the coast of Somalia continued.
[src:galley/2023-in-piracy] The hijacking of the *Ruen* by Somali pirates was their first successful attack on commercial shipping tankers since 2017.
[src:galley/2023-in-piracy] The Singapore Strait Gulf of Aden, Guardafui Channel and the Somali Sea were frequent targets of armed robbery, with the Gulf of Guinea reporting three of the four hijackings of the year.
[src:galley/2023-in-piracy] In December, Somali pirates waged four attacks on commercial ships.
[src:galley/2023-in-piracy] Hijackings only slightly increased from the previous year, from 115 to 120, yet with greater numbers of crew taken hostage and kidnapped in 2023.
[src:galley/2023-in-piracy] The IMB called for heightened caution for crew safety, with kidnappings steeply increased from 2022.
[src:galley/2023-in-piracy] In 2023, crew kidnappings increased sharply from 41 to 73.
[src:galley/2023-in-piracy] Pirate attacks of 2023 include events listed below; the list is not exhaustive.
[src:galley/2023-in-piracy] On March 25, the *Monjasa Reformer* Liberian-flagged tanker was hijacked in the Gulf of Guinea, about 140 nautical miles from Pointe Noire, Congo.
[src:galley/2023-in-piracy] Six kidnapped crew members were recovered May 8.
[src:galley/2023-in-piracy] On April 10, the *Success 9* Singaporean-flagged tanker was boarded in the Gulf of Guinea, about 300 nautical miles (556 km) off Cote d’Ivoire, then found six days later off Abidjan.
[src:galley/2023-in-piracy] On May 2, bulk carrier MV *Grebe Bulker*, under the ensign of Marshall Islands, was boarded in the Port of Owendo, Gabon, resulting in a hostage situation.
[src:galley/2023-in-piracy] The ship's captain, second mate and third mate were kidnapped.
[src:galley/2023-in-piracy] The hostages were released after 18 days in captivity.
[src:galley/2023-in-piracy] On November 19, 2023, *Galaxy Leader*, en route from Körfez, Turkey to Pipavav, India, and flagged under the ensign of Bahamas, was hijacked by Houthis in the Red Sea.
[src:galley/2023-in-piracy] Armed hijackers boarded the vessel by military helicopter.
[src:galley/2023-in-piracy] 25 crew were kidnapped, still remaining in captivity as at April 21, 2024.
[src:galley/2023-in-piracy] On November 22, Somali pirates hijacked the Iranian-flagged fishing dhow *Al-Meraj 1*, about 62 nautical miles south of the Ras Hafun peninsula, near the Qandala district of Puntland, with links between the hijackers and the Qandala district commander and other senior officials implicated.
[src:galley/2023-in-piracy] The vessel was boarded by a Somali clan militia, demanding $400,000 ransom.
[src:galley/2023-in-piracy] On November 26, Liberian-flagged oil tanker MV *Central Park* was seized off the coast of Yemen in the Gulf of Aden.
[src:galley/2023-in-piracy] Multilateral anti-piracy task force CTF 151 conducted a VBSS operation, rescuing MV *Central Park* and capturing the hijackers, suspected Somali pirates.
[src:galley/2023-in-piracy] On December 14, the first successful commercial ship hijacking since 2017 occurred off the coast of Somalia.
[src:galley/2023-in-piracy] Maltese-flagged MV *Ruen* was captured by Somali pirates.
[src:galley/2023-in-piracy] 17 crew were kidnapped, MV *Ruen* was rescued March 16, 2024, by the Indian Air Force.
[src:galley/2023-in-piracy] On December 22, 20 heavily armed Somali pirates hijacked a Yemeni fishing dhow, *Emarat-2*.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] Piracy surged in the Gulf of Aden at the start of the year.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] Increased incidents of piracy and hijacking in the Somali basin continued to be reported.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] When Houthis began attacking international shipping in the Red Sea, the year before, Somali pirates seized the opportunity to increase their attacks on ships off the Horn of Africa.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] Houthi attacks on ships in the Red Sea extended beyond the Gaza war to, as stated by a Houthi spokesman in January 2024, response to "American-British aggression against our country".
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] US Central Command then stated that the Houthi attacks "have nothing to do with the conflict in Gaza" and that Houthis had "fired indiscriminately into the Red Sea" to target vessels, affecting more than 40 nations.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] In March, shipping routes reported as the most dangerous in the world due to piracy (aside from hijackings and other incidents in the Red Sea and Gulf of Aden related to the Gaza war) were identified as: the Singapore Strait, Gulf of Guinea and the Strait of Malacca.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] 33 maritime piracy and armed robbery incidents against ships—during which 35 seafarers were taken hostage, and nine were kidnapped—were recorded in the first quarter of the year.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] From November 2023 to June 2024, more than 50 ships were attacked by Houthi rebels, resulting in the deaths of three sailors, and a hijacking.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] US military responded to the missile strikes in the Arabian and Red Seas with a series of attacks on the rebels' radar sites, which facilitated the targeting of maritime vessels; US Central Command reported seven radar sites destroyed in June.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] On 12 June, Houthi militants launched their first unmanned, remote-controlled USVs laden with explosives, sinking the *MV Tutor*, and killing one Filipino crewman.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] The following month, armed private maritime security contractors destroyed another Houthi drone boat as it approached the (unidentified) merchant ship that they were aboard.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] In September, the ICC IMB reported that sea piracy and armed robbery incidents were at the lowest levels recorded since 1994, though related crew safety risks persisted, due to sharp increases in kidnappings and in violence toward crew, as reported in July.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] While multilateral naval operations, increased vessel security, and improved navigation systems were generally enhanced, geopolitical tensions became an increasingly likely source of piracy incidents.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] Piracy events are noted as most common near the West African coast, in the Malacca Strait, and in the South China Sea in 2024.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] Pirate attacks of 2024 include events listed below; the list is not exhaustive.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] On January 29, the *INS Sumitra* rescued a hijacked fishing boat from Somalian pirates in the Gulf of Aden.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] On March 12, armed pirates in small boats attacked Bangladesh-flagged bulk carrier *MV Abdullah*.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] All 23 crew members aboard were taken hostage.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] Somali pirates released the vessel and crew on April 14, following payment of $5 million (€4.7 million) ransom.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] Later that month, India escorted the captured Somali pirates to stand trial for the hijacking the vessel and kidnapping of its crew in Mumbai.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] On April 4, the Panama-flagged *Magalie* was attacked in the Caribbean by two Haitian gangs: 5 Seconds and Taliban (unrelated to the Afghan Taliban).
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] The *Magalie* was captured by the armed gangs in the Varreux fuel terminal at Port-Au-Prince.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] The crew was taken hostage and a sixth of the cargo, consisting entirely of rice (the primary staple food of Haiti), was stolen.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] On April 7, the Haitian National Police stormed the seized freighter, ensuing in a five-hour gun battle with the gangs, in which two police officers were injured and several of the two gang's members turned pirate were killed.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] The ship, owned by U.S. shipping company Claude and Magalie, was recovered by the Haitian police force.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] The fate of the crew and any other seafarers aboard the *Magalie*, who were all taken hostage, remained unknown.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] On March 28, *Al-Kambar 786*, was boarded by nine armed pirates southwest of the Yemeni island of Socotra.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] *INS Sumedha* and *INS Trishul* intercepted the vessel on March 29.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] The Indian Navy engaged in "over 12 hours of intense coercive tactical measures" that led to the pirates' surrender.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] The pirates were taken to India to face prosecution under its Maritime Anti-Piracy Act 2022.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] Dry-bulk carrier MV *Tutor* was attacked in the Red Sea off Eritrea by the first seafaring Houthi unmanned, remote-controlled drone boat which was laden with explosives, on 12 June 2024, following two attacks a few hours apart, sinking on 18 June.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] An Indonesia-flagged tugboat, *Royal 17*, while towing a barge between ports on the island of Kalimantan in Borneo was hijacked and robbed on 20 September.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] All 14 crew were taken hostage and individually robbed by five armed and masked pirates, who also stole various equipment as well as cargo.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] Mistaken by Houthis as a British ship, Panama-flagged *Cordelia Moon* was hit by four missiles fired from a remotely piloted watercraft in the Red Sea on October 1, 2024.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] The tanker is owned by Amber Shipping Incorporated, and managed by Margao Marine Solutions, which is registered in India.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] In November 2024, protesting foreign boats fishing nearby waters, a group of "angry young local men in coastal communities" hijacked the *Liao Dong Yu 578*, part of a fleet known for illegal fishing off the coast.
[src:galley/2024-in-piracy] The vessel and crew were released in January 2025, after Chinese Ambassador Wang Yu delivered a $2 million ransom.
[src:galley/2025-in-piracy] The IMB reported that incidents of piracy had risen by 25% in Gulf of Guinea by the end of the third quarter of 2025.
[src:galley/2025-in-piracy] Overall, there was a nearly 50% rise in pirate attacks at sea over the previous year, increasing from 79 to 116 incidents during the same period, in which there were nine attempts to board vessels, with 102 ships boarded, four hijacked, and one fired upon.
[src:galley/2025-in-piracy] While under attack, 43 crew members were taken hostage, 16 were kidnapped, seven were threatened, with three assaulted and three injured.
[src:galley/2025-in-piracy] The Singapore Strait had a marked increase in piracy, with 73 incidents, curtailed by the arrests of two gangs by Indonesian police, in July.
[src:galley/2025-in-piracy] In January 2025 the *Liao Dong Yu 57* and its crew were released by hijackers (who had commandeered the vessel the previous November), after Chinese Ambassador Wang Yu delivered a $2 million ransom.
[src:galley/2025-in-piracy] The hijackers stated that "We are not pirates.
[src:galley/2025-in-piracy] The Marshall Islands-flagged *Talara* was seized by the Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps (IRGC) in the Strait of Hormuz on November 14, which diverted the oil products tanker to its territorial waters from the United Arab Emirates' coast, alleging "unauthorised cargo".
[src:galley/2025-in-piracy] The *Talara* had been en route to Singapore from the UAE port of Sharjah, carry a cargo of high-sulphur gasoil, a form of diesel fuel.
[src:galley/2025-in-piracy] The vessel is owned by Pasha Finance of Cypress, and managed by Columbia Shipmanagement, a Schoeller company.
[src:galley/2025-in-piracy] The IRGC released the tanker on November 19, without charge or any allegations, and all 21 crew found safe.
[src:galley/galley-p01] A **galley** is a type of ship optimised for propulsion by oars.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Galleys were historically used for warfare, trade, and piracy mostly in the seas surrounding Europe.
[src:galley/galley-p01] It developed in the Mediterranean world during antiquity and continued to exist in various forms until the early 19th century.
[src:galley/galley-p01] It typically had a long, slender hull, shallow draft, and often a low freeboard.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Most types of galleys also had sails that could be used in favourable winds, but they relied primarily on oars to move independently of winds and currents or in battle.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The term "galley" originated from a Greek term for a small type of galley and came in use in English from about 1300.
[src:galley/galley-p01] It has occasionally been used for unrelated vessels with similar military functions as galley but which were not Mediterranean in origin, such as medieval Scandinavian longships, 16th-century Acehnese ghalis and 18th-century North American gunboats.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Galleys were the primary warships used by the ancient Mediterranean naval powers, including the Phoenicians, Greeks and Romans.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The galley remained the dominant type of vessel used for war and piracy in the Mediterranean Sea until the start of the early modern period.
[src:galley/galley-p01] A final revival of galley warfare occurred during the 18th century in the Baltic Sea during the wars between Russia, Sweden, and Denmark.
[src:galley/galley-p01] In the Mediterranean, they remained in use until the very end of the 18th century, and survived in part because of their prestige and association with chivalry and land warfare.
[src:galley/galley-p01] In war, galleys were used in landing raids, as troop transports and were very effective in amphibious warfare.
[src:galley/galley-p01] While they usually served in wars or for defense against piracy, galleys also served as trade vessels for high-priority or expensive goods up to the end of the Middle Ages.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Its oars guaranteed that it could make progress where a sailing ship would have been becalmed, and its large crew could defend it against attacks from pirates and raiders.
[src:galley/galley-p01] This also made it one of the safest and most reliable forms of passenger transport, especially for Christian pilgrims during the High and Late Middle Ages.
[src:galley/galley-p01] For naval combat, galleys were equipped with various weapons: rams and occasionally catapults until late antiquity, Greek fire during the Early Middle Ages, and cannons from the 15th century.
[src:galley/galley-p01] However, they relied primarily on their large crews to overpower enemy vessels through boarding.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Galleys were the first vessels to effectively use heavy gunpowder artillery against other ships and naval fortifications.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Early 16th-century galleys had heavy guns in the bow which were aimed by manoeuvring the entire vessel.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Initially, gun galleys posed a serious threat to sailing warships, but were gradually made obsolete by the development of full-rigged ships with superior broadside armament.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Galleys were unsuitable in the wider ocean, far from land and bases of resupply.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Their role as flexible cruisers and patrol craft in the Mediterranean was also taken over by xebecs and other oar-sail hybrids.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Oars on ancient galleys were usually arranged in 15–30 pairs, from monoremes with a single line of oars to triremes with three lines of oars in a tiered arrangement.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Occasionally, much larger polyremes had multiple rowers per oar and hundreds of rowers per galley.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Ancient shipwrights built galleys using a labour-intensive, shell-first mortise and tenon technique up until the Early Middle Ages.
[src:galley/galley-p01] It was gradually replaced by a less expensive skeleton-first carvel method.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The rowing setup was also simplified and eventually developed into a system called **alla sensile** with up to three rowers sharing a single bench, handling one oar each.
[src:galley/galley-p01] This was suitable for skilled, professional rowers.
[src:galley/galley-p01] This was further simplified to the **a scaloccio** method with rowers sharing a bench but using just a single large oar, sometimes with up to seven or more rowers per oar in the very largest war galleys.
[src:galley/galley-p01] This method was more suitable for the use of forced labour, both galley slaves and convicts.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Most galleys were equipped with sails that could be used when the wind was favourable: basic square sails until the Early Middle Ages and later lateen sails.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The word *galley* has been attested in English from about 1300.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Variants of the same term were established in many other European languages from around 1500 both as a general term for oared warships or more specifically for the Mediterranean-style vessel.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The term derives from the Medieval Greek *galea*, a smaller version of the dromon, the prime warship of the Byzantine navy.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The origin of the Greek word is unclear but could possibly be related to *galeos*, the Greek word for dogfish shark.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Throughout history, there has been a wide variety of terms used for different types of galleys.
[src:galley/galley-p01] In modern historical literature, a galley is defined as a vessel relying primarily on oars, but which can also use sails when necessary, and which developed in the Mediterranean.
[src:galley/galley-p01] "Galley" is also occasionally used as a generic term for any type of oared vessels that are larger than boats and with similar functions but which are built according to other shipbuilding traditions.
[src:galley/galley-p01] It was only from the Late Middle Ages that a unified galley concept started to come into use.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Ancient galleys were named according to the number of oars, the number of banks of oars or rows of rowers.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The terms are based on contemporary language use combined with recent compounds of Greek and Latin words.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The earliest Greek single-banked galleys are called triaconters (from **triakontoroi**, "thirty-oars") and penteconters (**pentēkontoroi**, "fifty-oars").
[src:galley/galley-p01] For later galleys with more than one bank of oars, the terminology is based on Latin numerals with the suffix *-reme* from **rēmus**, "oar".
[src:galley/galley-p01] A *monoreme* has one bank of oars, a *bireme* two, and a *trireme* three.
[src:galley/galley-p01] A human-powered oared vessel is not practically feasible as four or more oars to a bank will either interfere with each other, or be too high above the waterline to be practicable.
[src:galley/galley-p01] In describing galleys, any number higher than three did not refer to banks of oars, but to additional rowers per oar.
[src:galley/galley-p01] *Quinquereme* (**quintus** + **rēmus**) was literally a "five-oar", but actually meant that there were more than one rower per oar in a bireme or trireme arrangement.
[src:galley/galley-p01] For simplicity, many modern scholars refer to these as "fives", "sixes", "eights", "elevens", etc.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Anything above six or seven rows of rowers was uncommon, but even an entirely unique "forty" has been attested from the 3rd century BC.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Any galley with more than three or four lines of rowers is often referred to as a "polyreme".
[src:galley/galley-p01] Medieval and early modern galleys were described based on the changing designs that evolved after the ancient designs and rowing arrangement had been forgotten.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Among the most important is the Byzantine dromon, the predecessor to the Italian *galea sottile*, the final form of the Mediterranean war galley.
[src:galley/galley-p01] As galleys became an integral part of an advanced, early modern system of warfare and state administration, they were divided into a number of ranked grades based on the size of the vessel and the number of its crew.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The most basic types were the large commander "lantern galleys", half-galleys, galiots, fustas, brigantines, and **fregatas**.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Naval historian Jan Glete has described these as a sort of predecessor of the later rating system of the Royal Navy and other sailing fleets in Northern Europe.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Classicist Lionel Casson has applied the term "galley" to oared Viking ships of the Early and High Middle Ages, both their well known longship warships and their less familiar merchant galleys.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Oared military vessels built on the British Isles in the 11th to 13th centuries were based on Scandinavian designs, but were referred to as "galleys" because of the similarity in function.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Many of them were similar to birlinns (a smaller version of the Highland galley), close relatives of longship types like the *snekkja*.
[src:galley/galley-p01] By the 14th century, they were replaced with balingers in southern Britain while longship-type Highland and Irish galleys and birlinns remained in use throughout the Middle Ages in northern Britain.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The French navy and the Royal Navy built a series of "galley frigates" from around 1670–1690 that were small two-decked sailing cruisers with a single row of oarports on the lower deck, close to the waterline.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The three British galley frigates also had distinctive names – *James Galley*, *Charles Galley*, and *Mary Galley*.
[src:galley/galley-p01] In the late 18th century, the term "galley" was sometimes used to describe small oared gun-armed vessels.
[src:galley/galley-p01] In North America, during the American Revolutionary War and other wars with France and Britain, the early US Navy and the navies they fought built vessels that were referred to "galleys" or "row galleys".
[src:galley/galley-p01] These are today best described as brigantines or Baltic-style gunboats.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The North American "galleys" were classified based on their military role, and in part due to technicalities in administration and naval financing.
[src:galley/galley-p01] In the latter part of the 19th century, the Royal Navy term for the gig reserved for the captain's use was "galley" even though it was issued to the ship by the navy dockyard as a "gig".
[src:galley/galley-p01] Among the earliest known watercraft were canoes made from hollowed-out logs, the earliest ancestors of galleys.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Their narrow hulls required them to be paddled in a fixed sitting position facing forward, a less efficient form of propulsion than rowing with proper oars, facing backward.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Seagoing paddled craft have been attested by finds of terracotta sculptures and lead models in the region of the Aegean Sea from the 3rd millennium BC.
[src:galley/galley-p01] However, archaeologists believe that the Stone Age colonization of islands in the Mediterranean around 8,000 BC required larger seaworthy vessels that were paddled and possibly even equipped with sails.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The first evidence of more complex craft considered prototypes for later galleys comes from Ancient Egypt during the Old Kingdom (about 2700–2200 BC).
[src:galley/galley-p01] Under the rule of pharaoh Pepi I (2332–2283 BC) these vessels were used to transport troops to raid settlements along the Levantine coast and to ship back slaves and timber.
[src:galley/galley-p01] During the reign of Hatshepsut (about 1479–1457 BC), Egyptian galleys traded in luxuries on the Red Sea with the enigmatic Land of Punt, as recorded on wall paintings at the Mortuary Temple of Hatshepsut at Deir el-Bahari.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The first Greek galley-like ships appeared around the second half of the 2nd millennium BC.
[src:galley/galley-p01] In the epic poem, the *Iliad*, set in the 12th century BC, oared vessels with a single row of oarmen were used primarily to transport soldiers between land battles.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The first recorded naval battle occurred as early as 1175 BC, the Battle of the Delta between Egyptian forces under Ramesses III and the enigmatic alliance known as the Sea Peoples.
[src:galley/galley-p01] It is the first known engagement between organized armed forces using sea vessels as weapons of war, though primarily as fighting platforms.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The Phoenicians were among the most significant naval civilizations in early classical antiquity, but little detailed evidence has been found of what kind of ships they used.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The best depictions found so far have been small, highly stylized images on seals which illustrate crescent-shaped vessels equipped with a single mast and bank of oars.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Colorful frescoes at the Minoan settlement on Santorini (about 1600 BC) depict vessels with tents arranged in a ceremonial procession.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Some of the vessels are rowed, but others are paddled.
[src:galley/galley-p01] This has been interpreted as a possible ritual reenactment of more ancient types of vessels, alluding to a time before rowing was invented.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Little is otherwise known about the use and design of Minoan ships.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Mediterranean galleys from around the 9th century BC typically had 15 and 25 pairs of oars ("triaconters" and "penteconters", respectively) with just one level of oars on each side, or "monoremes".
[src:galley/galley-p01] Sometime during the 8th century BC the first bireme galleys were built by adding a second level of rowers, one level above the other.
[src:galley/galley-p01] This created a second bank of oars, adding more propulsion power with the same length of hull.
[src:galley/galley-p01] It made galleys faster, more maneuverable and sturdier.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Phoenician shipbuilders were likely the first to build two-level galleys, and bireme designs were soon adopted and further developed by the Greeks.
[src:galley/galley-p01] A third bank of oar was added by attaching an outrigger to a bireme.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The outrigger was a projecting frame that gave additional leverage for a third rower to handle an oar efficiently.
[src:galley/galley-p01] It has been hypothesized that early forms of three-banked ships may have existed as early as 700 BC, but the earliest conclusive written reference dates to 542 BC.
[src:galley/galley-p01] These new galleys were called **triērēs** (literally "three-fitted") in Greek.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Romans later applied the term **triremis** which is the origin of "trireme" and the name used most commonly today.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Until at least the late 2nd century BC, there was no clear distinction between ships of trade and war other than how they were used.
[src:galley/galley-p01] River boats plied the waterways of ancient Egypt during the Old Kingdom (2700–2200 BC) and seagoing galley-like vessels were recorded bringing back luxuries from across the Red Sea in the reign of pharaoh Hatshepsut.
[src:galley/galley-p01] When rams or cutwaters were fitted to the bows of warships sometime around 700 BC, it resulted in a more distinct split between warships and trade ships.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Phoenicians used galleys for trade that were less elongated, carried fewer oars and relied more on sails.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Carthaginian trade galley wrecks found off Sicily that date to the 3rd or 2nd century BC had a length to breadth ratio of 6:1, proportions that fell between the 4:1 of sailing merchant ships and the 8:1 or 10:1 of war galleys.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Most of the surviving documentary evidence comes from Greek and Roman shipping, though it is likely that merchant galleys all over the Mediterranean were highly similar.
[src:galley/galley-p01] In Greek they were referred to as **histiokopos** ("sail-oar-er") to reflect that they relied on both types of propulsion.
[src:galley/galley-p01] In Latin they were called *actuaria (navis)*, "(ship) that moves", stressing that they were capable of making progress regardless of weather conditions.
[src:galley/galley-p01] As an example of the speed and reliability, during an instance of the famous "Carthago delenda est" speech, Cato the Elder demonstrated the close proximity of the Roman arch enemy Carthage by displaying a fresh fig to his audience that he claimed had been picked in North Africa only three days past.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Other cargoes carried by galleys were honey, cheese, meat, and live animals intended for gladiator combat.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The Romans had several types of merchant galleys that specialized in various tasks, out of which the **actuaria** with up to 50 rowers was the most versatile, including the **phaselus** (lit.
[src:galley/galley-p01] "bean pod") for passenger transport and the **lembus**, a small-scale express carrier.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Many of these designs continued to be used until the Middle Ages.
[src:galley/galley-p01] After the fall of the Western Roman Empire around the 5th century AD, the old Mediterranean economy collapsed and the volume of trade went down drastically.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The Eastern Roman Empire neglected to revive overland trade routes, but was dependent on keeping the sea lanes open to keep the empire together.
[src:galley/galley-p01] In 600–750 AD bulk trade declined while luxury trade increased.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Galleys remained in service, but were profitable mainly in the luxury trade, which set off their high maintenance cost.
[src:galley/galley-p01] In the 10th century, there was a sharp increase in piracy which resulted in larger trade ships with more numerous crews.
[src:galley/galley-p01] These were mostly built by the growing maritime republics of Italy which were emerging as the dominant sea powers, including Venice, Genoa, and Pisa.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Their merchant galleys were similar to dromons, but without heavy weapons and both faster and wider.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The largest types were used by Venice, based on galley types like the **pamphylon** and **chelandion**.
[src:galley/galley-p01] They had tower-like superstructures and could be manned by crews of up to 1,000 men and could be employed in warfare when required.
[src:galley/galley-p01] A further boost to the development of the large merchant galleys was the increase in Western European pilgrims traveling to the Holy Land.
[src:galley/galley-p01] In Northern Europe, Viking longships and their derivations, knarrs, dominated trading and shipping.
[src:galley/galley-p01] They functioned and were propelled similar to the Mediterranean galleys, but developed from a separate building tradition.
[src:galley/galley-p01] In the Mediterranean, merchant galleys continued to be used during the High and Late Middle Ages, even as sailing vessels evolved more efficient hulls and rigging.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The zenith in the design of merchant galleys came with the state-owned "great galleys" of the Venetian Republic, first built in the 1290s.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The great galleys were in all respects larger than contemporary war galleys (up to 46 m) and had a deeper draft, with more room for cargo (140–250 tonnes).
[src:galley/galley-p01] With a full complement of rowers ranging from 150 to 180 men, all available to defend the ship from attack, they were also very safe modes of travel.
[src:galley/galley-p01] This attracted a business of carrying rich pilgrims to the Holy Land, a trip that could be accomplished in as little 29 days on the route Venice–Jaffa, despite landfalls for rest and watering, or to shelter from rough weather.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Later routes linked ports around the Mediterranean, between the Mediterranean and the Black Sea, and between the Mediterranean and Bruges.
[src:galley/galley-p01] In 1447 Florentine galleys could stop at as many as 14 ports on their way to and from Alexandria in Egypt.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The earliest use for galleys in warfare was to ferry fighters from one place to another, and until the middle of the 2nd millennium BC had no real distinction from merchant freighters.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Around the 14th century BC, the first dedicated fighting ships were developed, sleeker and with cleaner lines than the bulkier merchants.
[src:galley/galley-p01] They were used for raiding, capturing merchants and for dispatches.
[src:galley/galley-p01] During this early period, raiding became the most important form of organized violence in the Mediterranean region.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Casson used the example of Homer's works to show that seaborne raiding was considered a common and legitimate occupation among ancient maritime peoples.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The later Athenian historian Thucydides described it as having been "without stigma" before his time.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The development of the ram sometime before the 8th century BC changed the nature of naval warfare, which had until then been a matter of boarding and hand-to-hand fighting.
[src:galley/galley-p01] With a heavy projection at the foot of the bow, sheathed with metal, usually bronze, a ship could incapacitate an enemy ship by punching a hole in its planking.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The relative speed and nimbleness of ships became important, since a slower ship could be outmaneuvered and disabled by a faster one.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The earliest designs had only one row of rowers that sat in undecked hulls, rowing against thole pins, or oarports, that were placed directly along the railings.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The practical upper limit for wooden constructions fast and maneuverable enough for warfare was around 25–30 oars per side.
[src:galley/galley-p01] By adding another level of oars, a development that occurred no later than c.
[src:galley/galley-p01] 750 BC, the galley could be made shorter with as many rowers, while making them strong enough to be effective ramming weapons.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The emergence of more advanced states and intensified competition between them spurred on the development of advanced galleys with multiple banks of rowers.
[src:galley/galley-p01] During the middle of the first millennium BC, the Mediterranean powers developed successively larger and more complex vessels, the most advanced being the classical trireme with up to 170 rowers.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Triremes fought several important engagements in the naval battles of the Greco-Persian Wars (502–449 BC) and the Peloponnesian War (431–404 BC), including the Battle of Aegospotami in 405 BC, which sealed the defeat of Athens by Sparta and its allies.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The trireme was an advanced ship that was expensive to build and to maintain due its large crew.
[src:galley/galley-p01] By the 5th century, advanced war galleys had been developed that required sizable states with an advanced economy to build and maintain.
[src:galley/galley-p01] It was associated with the latest in warship technology around the 4th century BC and could only be employed by an advanced state with an advanced economy and administration.
[src:galley/galley-p01] They required considerable skill to row and oarsmen were mostly free citizens who had years of experience at the oar.
[src:galley/galley-p01] As civilizations around the Mediterranean grew in size and complexity, both their navies and the galleys that made up their numbers became successively larger.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The basic design of two or three rows of oars remained the same, but more rowers were added to each oar.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The exact reasons are not known, but are believed to have been caused by addition of more troops and the use of more advanced ranged weapons on ships, such as catapults.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The size of the new naval forces also made it difficult to find enough skilled rowers for the one-man-per-oar system of the earliest triremes.
[src:galley/galley-p01] With more than one man per oar, a single rower could set the pace for the others to follow, meaning that more unskilled rowers could be employed.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The successor states of Alexander the Great's empire built galleys that were like triremes or biremes in oar layout, but manned with additional rowers for each oar.
[src:galley/galley-p01] 432–367 BC) is credited with pioneering the "five" and "six", meaning five or six rows of rowers plying two or three rows of oars.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Ptolemy II (283–46 BC) is known to have built a large fleet of very large galleys with several experimental designs rowed by everything from 12 up to 40 rows of rowers, though most of these are considered to have been quite impractical.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Fleets with large galleys were put in action in conflicts such as the Punic Wars (246–146 BC) between the Roman Republic and Carthage, which included massive naval battles with hundreds of vessels and tens of thousands of soldiers, seamen, and rowers.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The Battle of Actium in 31 BC between the forces of Augustus and Mark Antony marked the peak of the Roman fleet arm.
[src:galley/galley-p01] After Augustus' victory at Actium, most of the Roman fleet was dismantled and burned.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The Roman civil wars were fought mostly by land forces, and from the 160s until the 4th century AD, no major fleet actions were recorded.
[src:galley/galley-p01] During this time, most of the galley crews were disbanded or employed for entertainment purposes in mock battles or in handling the sail-like sun-screens in the larger Roman arenas.
[src:galley/galley-p01] What fleets remained were treated as auxiliaries of the land forces, and galley crewmen themselves called themselves **milites**, "soldiers", rather than **nautae**, "sailors".
[src:galley/galley-p01] The Roman galley fleets were turned into provincial patrol forces that were smaller and relied largely on *liburnians*, compact biremes with 25 pairs of oars.
[src:galley/galley-p01] These were named after an Illyrian tribe known by Romans for their sea roving practices, and these smaller craft were based on, or inspired by, their vessels of choice.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The liburnians and other small galleys patrolled the rivers of continental Europe and reached as far as the Baltic, where they were used to fight local uprisings and assist in checking foreign invasions.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The Romans maintained numerous bases around the empire: along the rivers of Central Europe, chains of forts along the northern European coasts and the British Isles, Mesopotamia, and North Africa, including Trabzon, Vienna, Belgrade, Dover, Seleucia, and Alexandria.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Few actual galley battles in the provinces are found in records.
[src:galley/galley-p01] One action in 70 AD at the unspecified location of the "Island of the Batavians" during the Batavian Rebellion was recorded, and included a trireme as the Roman flagship.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The last provincial fleet, the *classis Britannica*, was reduced by the late 200s, though there was a minor upswing under the rule of Constantine (272–337).
[src:galley/galley-p01] His rule also saw the last major naval battle of the unified Roman Empire (before the permanent split into Western and Eastern [later "Byzantine"] Empires), the Battle of the Hellespont of 324.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Some time after the Battle of the Hellespont, the classical trireme fell out of use, and its design was forgotten.
[src:galley/galley-p01] A transition from galley to sailing vessels as the most common types of warships began in the High Middle Ages (c.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Large high-sided sailing ships had always been formidable obstacles for galleys.
[src:galley/galley-p01] To low-freeboard oared vessels, the bulkier sailing ships, the cog and the carrack, were almost like floating fortresses, being difficult to board and even harder to capture.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Galleys remained useful as warships throughout the entire Middle Ages because of their maneuverability.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Sailing ships of the time had only one mast, usually with just a single, large square sail.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Though equipped to beat to windward, their performance at this would have been limited.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Galleys were therefore important for coastal raiding and amphibious landings, both key elements of medieval warfare.
[src:galley/galley-p01] In the eastern Mediterranean, the Byzantine Empire struggled with the incursion from invading Muslim Arabs from the 7th century, leading to fierce competition, a buildup of fleet, and war galleys of increasing size.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Soon after conquering Egypt and the Levant, the Arab rulers built ships highly similar to Byzantine dromons with the help of local Coptic shipwrights from former Byzantine naval bases.
[src:galley/galley-p01] By the 9th century, the struggle between the Byzantines and Arabs had turned the Eastern Mediterranean into a no-man's land for merchant activity.
[src:galley/galley-p01] In the 820s Crete was captured by Al-Andalus Muslims who had fled a failed revolt against the Emirate of Cordoba, turning the island into a base for (galley) attacks on Christian shipping until the island was recaptured by the Byzantines in 960.
[src:galley/galley-p01] In the western Mediterranean and Atlantic, the division of the Carolingian Empire in the late 9th century brought on a period of instability, meaning increased piracy and raiding in the Mediterranean, particularly by newly arrived Muslim invaders.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The situation was worsened by raiding Scandinavian Vikings who used longships, vessels that in many ways were very close to galleys in design and functionality and also employed similar tactics.
[src:galley/galley-p01] To counter the threat, local rulers began to build large oared vessels, some with up to 30 pairs of oars, that were larger, faster, and with higher sides than Viking ships.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Scandinavian expansion, including incursions into the Mediterranean and attacks on both Muslim Iberia and even Constantinople itself, subsided by the mid-11th century.
[src:galley/galley-p01] By this time, greater stability in merchant traffic was achieved by the emergence of Christian kingdoms such as those of France, Hungary, and Poland.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Around the same time, Italian port towns and city states, like Venice, Pisa, and Amalfi, rose on the fringes of the Byzantine Empire as it struggled with eastern threats.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Late medieval maritime warfare was divided in two distinct regions.
[src:galley/galley-p01] In the Mediterranean galleys were used for raiding along coasts, and in the constant fighting for naval bases.
[src:galley/galley-p01] In the Atlantic and Baltic there was greater focus on sailing ships that were used mostly for troop transport, with galleys providing fighting support.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Galleys were still widely used in the north and were the most numerous warships used by Mediterranean powers with interests in the north, especially France, the Iberian kingdoms and the Italian merchant republics.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The kings of France operated the *Clos de Galées* (literally "galley enclosure") in Rouen during the 14th and 15th century where they had southern-style war galleys built .
[src:galley/galley-p01] The *Clos* was built by Genoese in 1298 and they continued to dominate shipbuilding there until its destruction in 1419 so that they wouldn't fall into English hands.
[src:galley/galley-p01] During the 13th and 14th century, the galley evolved into the design that was to remain essentially the same until it was phased out in the early 19th century.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The new type descended from the ships used by Byzantine and Muslim fleets in the Early Middle Ages.
[src:galley/galley-p01] These were the mainstay of all Christian powers until the 14th century, including the great maritime republics of Genoa and Venice, the Papacy, the Hospitallers, Aragon, and Castile, as well as by various pirates and corsairs.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The overall term used for these types of vessels was **gallee sottili** ("slender galleys").
[src:galley/galley-p01] The later Ottoman navy used similar designs, but they were generally faster under sail, and smaller, but slower under oars.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Galley designs were intended solely for close action with hand-held weapons and projectile weapons like bows and crossbows.
[src:galley/galley-p01] In the 13th century the Iberian Crown of Aragon built several fleet of galleys (known as Catalan galleys) with high castles, manned with Catalan crossbowmen, and regularly defeated numerically superior Angevin forces.
[src:galley/galley-p01] During the early 15th century, sailing ships began to dominate naval warfare in northern waters.
[src:galley/galley-p01] A Castilian naval raid on the island of Jersey in 1405 employed a naval force consisting mostly of cogs or carracks, rather than the oared-powered galleys.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The sailing vessel was always at the mercy of the wind for propulsion, and those that did carry oars were placed at a disadvantage because they were not optimized for oar use.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The galley did have disadvantages compared to the sailing vessel though.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Their smaller hulls were not able to hold as much cargo and this limited their range as the crews were required to replenish food stuffs more frequently.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The low freeboard of the galley meant that in close action with a sailing vessel, the sailing vessel would usually maintain a height advantage.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The sailing vessel could also fight more effectively farther out at sea and in rougher wind conditions because of the height of their freeboard.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Under sail, an oared warship was placed at much greater risk as a result of the piercings for the oars which were required to be near the waterline and would allow water to ingress into the galley if the vessel heeled too far to one side.
[src:galley/galley-p01] These advantages and disadvantages led the galley to be and remain a primarily coastal vessel.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The shift to sailing vessels in the Mediterranean was the result of the negation of some of the galley's advantages as well as the adoption of gunpowder weapons on a much larger institutional scale.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The sailing vessel was propelled in a different manner than the galley but the tactics were often the same until the 16th century.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The real-estate afforded to the sailing vessel to place larger cannons and other armament mattered little because early gunpowder weapons had limited range and were expensive to produce.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The eventual creation of cast iron cannons allowed vessels and armies to be outfitted much more cheaply.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The cost of gunpowder also fell in this period.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The armament of both vessel types varied between larger weapons such as bombards and the smaller swivel guns.
[src:galley/galley-p01] For logistical purposes it became convenient for those with larger shore establishments to standardize upon a given size of cannon.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Traditionally the English in the North and the Venetians in the Mediterranean are seen as some the earliest to move in this direction.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The improving sail rigs of northern vessels also allowed them to navigate in the coastal waters of the Mediterranean to a much larger degree than before.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Aside from warships the decrease in the cost of gunpowder weapons also led to the arming of merchants.
[src:galley/galley-p01] The larger vessels of the north continued to mature while the galley retained its defining characteristics.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Attempts were made to stave this off such as the addition of fighting castles in the bow, but such additions to counter the threats brought by larger sailing vessels often offset the advantages of galley.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Attempts to combine the advantages of both rowing and sailing ships were done in the 16th century, resulting in galleasses.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Despite their common name, their different types entailed different to one or another design.
[src:galley/galley-p01] Venetian galleasses were particularly large and powerful galleys with hulls more akin to sailing ships, while in turn, Spanish Atlantic galleasses were essentially sailing ships fitted with a line of rows, which would be used strategically to assist maneuver and sprint while in battle.
[src:galley/galley-p02] From around 1450, three major naval powers established a dominance over different parts of the Mediterranean, using galleys as their primary weapons at sea: the Ottomans in the east, Venice in the center and Habsburg Spain in the west.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The core of their fleets were concentrated in the three major, wholly dependable naval bases in the Mediterranean: Constantinople, Venice, and Barcelona.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The main difference between the Christan and Ottoman galley navies laid on quality against quantity.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Western galley squads proved tactically superior, as noted in both Spanish and Turkish sources, but in turn, Constantinople could put out immense numbers of ships and crews.
[src:galley/galley-p02] In 1564, García de Toledo wrote in his report that Christians could only trust on mobile attacks rather than seeking frontal battle.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Major encounters involved necessarily alliances between Venice, Spain and the Spanish satellites in Italy in order to match the Ottoman naval potency.
[src:galley/galley-p02] This created an uniquely unequal relationship, as Venice depended on Spain and its allies for defense against Ottoman expansionism, but would rarely help them in the opposite case.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Naval warfare in the 16th-century Mediterranean was fought mostly on smaller scale, with raiding and minor actions dominating.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Ottoman Barbary corsairs launched attacks on lightly defended coastal settlements, while the Christian Knights Hospitaller against politically relevant targets in the Levant.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Only three truly major fleet engagements were actually fought in the 16th century: the battles of Preveza in 1538, Djerba in 1560, and Lepanto in 1571.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Lepanto became the last large all-galley battle ever, and was also one of the largest battle in sheer number of participants in early modern Europe before the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Spain maintained four permanent galley squadrons to guard its coasts and trade routes against the Ottomans, the French, and their corsairs.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Together they formed the largest stable galley navy in the Mediterranean in the early 17th century.
[src:galley/galley-p02] They were the backbone of the Spanish Mediterranean war fleet and were used for ferrying troops, supplies, horses, and munitions to Spain's Italian and African possessions.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Galleys were also fielded in conjunction with sailing ships like galleons and carracks, such as in the relief of Coron, where their Genoese admiral Andrea Doria used galleys to assist his sailing ships in lack of wind.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The Spanish also used galley forces for conflicts outside the Mediterranean, including deployments in their colonial possessions in the Caribbean and the Philippines to hunt pirates, and sporadically used them in the Netherlands and the Bay of Biscay.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Their admiral Álvaro de Bazán the Elder also designed and built Atlantic galleasses, essentially galleons with rows, to hunt down pirates and foreign privateers.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Spain also sent galley squadrons to the Netherlands during the Eighty Years' War which successfully operated against Dutch forces in the enclosed, shallow coastal waters.
[src:galley/galley-p02] From the late 1560s, galleys were also used to transport silver to Genoese bankers to finance Spanish troops against the Dutch uprising.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Mediterranean galleasses and galleys were part of an invasion force of over 16,000 men under Álvaro de Bazán the Younger that conquered the Azores in 1583.
[src:galley/galley-p02] During this conquest, captain Diego de Medrano is noted for innovating naval warfare techniques by enhancing the design of his galleys, becoming the first person to successfully cross the ocean with this type of galley.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Around 2,000 galley rowers under the command of Medrano were on board ships of the famous 1588 Spanish Armada, though few of these actually made it to the battle itself.
[src:galley/galley-p02] At the end of the 17th century, galleys called periaguas were fielded to deal with foreign pirates and privateers in Spanish Caribbean.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Spanish privateers specialized in countering piracy, the *guarda costa*, used periaguas to chase their sailing ships against the wind or to conduct night attacks on them.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Ottoman galleys contested the Portuguese intrusion in the Indian Ocean in the 16th century, but failed against the high-sided, massive Portuguese carracks in open waters.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Even though the carracks themselves were soon surpassed by other types of sailing vessels, their greater range, great size, and high superstructures, armed with numerous wrought iron guns easily outmatched the short-ranged, low-freeboard Turkish galleys.
[src:galley/galley-p02] In Southeast Asia during the 16th and early 17th century, the Aceh Sultanate had fleets of up to 100 native galley-like vessels (ghali) as well as smaller rowed vessels, there were described by Europeans as lancarans, galliots, and fustas.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Some of the larger vessels were very large with heavier armament than standard Mediterranean galleys, with raised platforms for infantry and some with stern structures similar in height to that of contemporary galleons.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Galleys had been synonymous with warships in the Mediterranean for at least 2,000 years, and continued to fulfill that role with the invention of gunpowder and heavy artillery.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Though early 20th-century historians often dismissed the galleys as hopelessly outclassed with the first introduction of naval artillery on sailing ships, it was the galley that was favored by the introduction of heavy naval guns.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Galleys were a more "mature" technology with long-established tactics and traditions of supporting social institutions and naval organizations.
[src:galley/galley-p02] In combination with the intensified conflicts this led to a substantial increase in the size of galley fleets from c.
[src:galley/galley-p02] 1520–80, above all in the Mediterranean, but also in other European theatres.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Galleys and similar oared vessels remained uncontested as the most effective gun-armed warships in theory until the 1560s, and in practice for a few decades more, and were actually considered a grave risk to sailing warships.
[src:galley/galley-p02] They could effectively fight other galleys, attack sailing ships in calm weather or in unfavorable winds (or deny them action if needed) and act as floating siege batteries.
[src:galley/galley-p02] They were also unequaled in their amphibious capabilities, even at extended ranges, as exemplified by French interventions as far north as Scotland in the mid-16th century.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Heavy artillery on galleys was mounted in the bow, which aligned easily with the long-standing tactical tradition of attacking head on, bow first.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The ordnance on galleys was heavy from its introduction in the 1480s, and capable of quickly demolishing the high, thin medieval stone walls that still prevailed in the 16th century.
[src:galley/galley-p02] This temporarily upended the strength of older seaside fortresses, which had to be rebuilt to cope with gunpowder weapons.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The addition of guns also improved the amphibious abilities of galleys as they could make assaults supported with heavy firepower, and were even more effectively defended when beached stern-first.
[src:galley/galley-p02] An accumulation and generalizing of bronze cannons and small firearms in the Mediterranean during the 16th century increased the cost of warfare, but also made those dependent on them more resilient to manpower losses.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Older ranged weapons, like bows or even crossbows, required considerable skill to handle, sometimes a lifetime of practice, while gunpowder weapons required considerably less training to use successfully.
[src:galley/galley-p02] According to an influential study by military historian John F.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Guilmartin, this transition in warfare, along with the introduction of much cheaper cast iron guns in the 1580s, proved the "death knell" for the war galley as a significant military vessel.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Gunpowder weapons began to displace men as the fighting power of armed forces, making individual soldiers more deadly and effective.
[src:galley/galley-p02] As offensive weapons, firearms could be stored for years with minimal maintenance and did not require the expenses associated with soldiers.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Manpower could thus be exchanged for capital investments, something which benefited sailing vessels that were already far more economical in their use of manpower.
[src:galley/galley-p02] It also served to increase their strategic range and to out-compete galleys as fighting ships.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Skillful usage of guns in galley warfare was seen in the Battle of the Gulf of Tunis, where Spanish and Italian galleys under Álvaro de Bazán y Benavides engaged and overwhelmed Barbary galleons thanks to the superior range of their own cannons.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Atlantic-style warfare based on large, heavily armed sailing ships began to change naval warfare in the Mediterranean in the early 17th century.
[src:galley/galley-p02] In 1616, a small Spanish squadron of six sailing ships cruised the eastern Mediterranean and defeated an Ottoman fleet of 55 galleys at the Battle of Cape Gelidonya.
[src:galley/galley-p02] An example of this was when a Spanish fleet used its galleys in a mixed naval/amphibious battle in the second 1641 battle of Tarragona, to break a French naval blockade and land troops and supplies.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Even the Venetians, Ottomans, and other Mediterranean powers began to build Atlantic style warships for use in the Mediterranean in the latter part of the century.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Christian and Muslim corsairs had been using galleys in sea roving and in support of the major powers in times of war, but largely replaced them with xebecs, various sail/oar hybrids, and a few remaining light galleys in the early 17th century.
[src:galley/galley-p02] No large all-galley battles were fought after the gigantic clash at Lepanto in 1571, and galleys were mostly used as cruisers or for supporting sailing warships as a rearguard in fleet actions, similar to the duties performed by frigates outside the Mediterranean.
[src:galley/galley-p02] They could assist damaged ships out of the line, but generally only in very calm weather, as was the case at the Battle of Málaga in 1704.
[src:galley/galley-p02] They could also defeat larger ships that were isolated, as when in 1651 a squadron of Spanish galleys captured a French galleon at Formentera.
[src:galley/galley-p02] For small states and principalities as well as groups of private merchants, galleys were more affordable than large and complex sailing warships, and were used as defense against piracy.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Galleys required less timber to build, the design was relatively simple and they carried fewer guns.
[src:galley/galley-p02] They were tactically flexible and could be used for naval ambushes as well amphibious operations.
[src:galley/galley-p02] They also required few skilled seamen and were difficult for sailing ships to catch, but vital in hunting down and catching other galleys and oared raiders.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Among the largest galley fleets in the 17th century were operated by the two major Mediterranean powers, France and Spain.
[src:galley/galley-p02] France had by the 1650s become the most powerful state in Europe, and expanded its galley forces under the rule of the absolutist "Sun King" Louis XIV.
[src:galley/galley-p02] In the 1690s the French galley corps (**corps des galères**) reached its all-time peak with more than 50 vessels manned by over 15,000 men and officers, becoming the largest galley fleet in the world at the time.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Although there was intense rivalry between France and Spain, not a single galley battle occurred between the two great powers during this period, and virtually no naval battles between other nations either.
[src:galley/galley-p02] During the War of the Spanish Succession, French galleys were involved in actions against Antwerp and Harwich, but due to the intricacies of alliance politics there were never any Franco-Spanish galley clashes.
[src:galley/galley-p02] In the first half of the 18th century, the other major naval powers in the Mediterranean Sea, the Order of Saint John based in Malta, and of the Papal States in central Italy, cut down drastically on their galley forces.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Despite the lack of action, the galley corps received vast resources (25–50% of the French naval expenditures) during the 1660s.
[src:galley/galley-p02] It was maintained as a functional fighting force right up until its abolition in 1748, though its primary function was more of a symbol of Louis XIV's absolutist ambitions.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The last recorded battle in the Mediterranean where galleys played a significant part was at Matapan in 1717, between the Ottomans and Venice and its allies, though they had little influence on the outcome.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Few large-scale naval battles were fought in the Mediterranean throughout most of the remainder of the 18th century.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The Tuscan galley fleet was dismantled around 1718, Naples had only four old vessels by 1734 and the French Galley Corps had ceased to exist as an independent arm in 1748.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Venice, the Papal States, and the Knights of Malta were the only state fleets that maintained galleys, though in nothing like their previous quantities.
[src:galley/galley-p02] By 1790, there were fewer than 50 galleys in service among all the Mediterranean powers, half of which belonged to Venice.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Oared vessels remained in use in northern waters for a long time, though in subordinate role and in particular circumstances.
[src:galley/galley-p02] In the Italian Wars, French galleys brought up from the Mediterranean to the Atlantic posed a serious threat to the early English Tudor navy during coastal operations.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The response came in the building of a considerable fleet of oared vessels, including hybrids with a complete three-masted rig, as well as a Mediterranean-style galleys (that were even attempted to be manned with convicts and slaves).
[src:galley/galley-p02] Under King Henry VIII, the English navy used several kinds of vessels that were adapted to local needs.
[src:galley/galley-p02] English *galliasses* (very different from the Mediterranean vessel of the same name) were employed to cover the flanks of larger naval forces while *pinnaces* and *rowbarges* were used for scouting or even as a backup for the longboats and tenders for the larger sailing ships.
[src:galley/galley-p02] During the Dutch Revolt (1566–1609) both the Dutch and Spanish found galleys useful for amphibious operations in the many shallow waters around the Low Countries where deep-draft sailing vessels could not enter.
[src:galley/galley-p02] While galleys were too vulnerable to be used in large numbers in the open waters of the Atlantic, they were well-suited for use in much of the Baltic Sea by Denmark-Norway, Sweden, Russia, and some of the Central European powers with ports on the southern coast.
[src:galley/galley-p02] There were two types of naval battlegrounds in the Baltic.
[src:galley/galley-p02] One was the open sea, suitable for large sailing fleets; the other was the coastal areas and especially the chain of small islands and archipelagos that ran almost uninterrupted from Stockholm to the Gulf of Finland.
[src:galley/galley-p02] In these areas, conditions were often too calm, cramped, and shallow for sailing ships, but they were excellent for galleys and other oared vessels.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Galleys of the Mediterranean type were first introduced in the Baltic Sea around the mid-16th century as competition between the Scandinavian states of Denmark and Sweden intensified.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The Swedish galley fleet was the largest outside the Mediterranean, and served as an auxiliary branch of the army.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Very little is known about the design of Baltic Sea galleys, except that they were overall smaller than in the Mediterranean and they were rowed by army soldiers rather than convicts or slaves.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Galleys were introduced to the Baltic Sea in the 16th century but the details of their designs are lacking due to the absence of records.
[src:galley/galley-p02] They might have been built in a more regional style, but the only known depiction from the time shows a typical Mediterranean style vessel.
[src:galley/galley-p02] There is conclusive evidence that Denmark-Norway became the first Baltic power to build classic Mediterranean-style galleys in the 1660s, though they proved to be generally too large to be useful in the shallow waters of the Baltic archipelagos.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Sweden and especially Russia began to launch galleys and various rowed vessels in great numbers during the Great Northern War in the first two decades of the 18th century.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Sweden and Russia became the two main competitors for Baltic dominance in the 18th century, and built the largest galley fleets in the world at the time.
[src:galley/galley-p02] They were used for amphibious operations in Russo-Swedish wars of 1741–43 and 1788–90.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The last galleys ever constructed were built in 1796 by Russia, and remained in service well into the 19th century, but saw little action.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The last time galleys were deployed in action was when the Russian navy was attacked in Åbo (Turku) in 1854 as part of the Crimean War.
[src:galley/galley-p02] In the second half of the 18th century, the role of Baltic galleys in coastal fleets was replaced first with hybrid "archipelago frigates" (such as the turuma or pojama) and xebecs, and after the 1790s with various types of gunboats.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The documentary evidence for the construction of ancient galleys is fragmentary, particularly in pre-Roman times.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Plans and schematics in the modern sense did not exist until around the 17th century and nothing comparable has survived from ancient times.
[src:galley/galley-p02] How galleys were constructed has therefore been a matter of looking at circumstantial evidence in literature, art, coinage and monuments that include ships, some of them actually in natural size.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Since the war galleys floated even with a ruptured hull and virtually never had any ballast or heavy cargo that could sink them, almost no wrecks have so far been found.
[src:galley/galley-p02] These vessels have only one mast and vertical stems and sternposts, with the front decorated with an Eye of Horus, the first example of such a decoration.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The eye was later used by other Mediterranean cultures to decorate seagoing craft in the belief that it helped to guide the ship safely to its destination.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The early Egyptian vessels apparently lacked a keel.
[src:galley/galley-p02] To provide a stiffening along its length, they had large cables, trusses, connecting stem and stern resting on massive crutches on deck.
[src:galley/galley-p02] They were held in tension to avoid hogging while at sea (bending the ship's construction upward in the middle).
[src:galley/galley-p02] In the 15th century BC, Egyptian galley-like craft were still depicted with the distinctive extreme sheer, but had by then developed the distinctive forward-curving stern decorations with ornaments in the shape of lotus flowers.
[src:galley/galley-p02] They had possibly developed a primitive type of keel, but still retained the large cables intended to prevent hogging.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The construction of the earliest oared vessels is mostly unknown and highly conjectural.
[src:galley/galley-p02] They likely used a mortise construction, but were sewn together rather than pinned together with nails and dowels.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Being completely open, they were rowed (or even paddled) from the open deck, and likely had "ram entries", projections from the bow lowered the resistance of moving through water, making them slightly more hydrodynamic.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The first true galleys, the triaconters (literally "thirty-oarers") and penteconters ("fifty-oarers") were developed from these early designs and set the standard for the larger designs that would come later.
[src:galley/galley-p02] They were rowed on only one level, which made them fairly slow, likely only about 10 km/h (6 mph).
[src:galley/galley-p02] By the 8th century BC the first galleys rowed at two levels had been developed, among the earliest being the two-level penteconters which were considerably shorter than the one-level equivalents, and therefore more maneuverable.
[src:galley/galley-p02] They were an estimated 25 m in length and displaced 15 tonnes with 25 pairs of oars.
[src:galley/galley-p02] These could have reached an estimated top speed of up to 14 km/h (9 mph), making them the first genuine warships when fitted with bow rams.
[src:galley/galley-p02] They were equipped with a single square sail on mast set roughly halfway along the length of the hull.
[src:galley/galley-p02] By the 5th century BC, the first *triremes* were in use by various powers in the eastern Mediterranean.
[src:galley/galley-p02] This was a fully developed, highly specialized war galley that was capable of high speeds and complex maneuvers.
[src:galley/galley-p02] At nearly 40 m in length, displacing up to 50 tonnes, it was more than three times as expensive to build as a two-level penteconter.
[src:galley/galley-p02] A trireme also had an additional mast with a smaller square sail placed near the bow.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Up to 170 oarsmen sat on three levels with one oar each that varied slightly in length.
[src:galley/galley-p02] To accommodate three levels of oars, rowers sat staggered on three levels.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Arrangements of the three levels are believed to have varied, but the most well-documented design made use of a projecting structure, or outrigger, where the oarlock in the form of a *thole pin* was placed.
[src:galley/galley-p02] This allowed the outermost row of oarsmen enough leverage for full strokes that made efficient use of their oars.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The first dedicated war galleys fitted with rams were built with a mortise and tenon technique, a so-called *shell-first* method.
[src:galley/galley-p02] In this, the planking of the hull was strong enough to hold the ship together structurally, and was also watertight without the need for caulking.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Hulls had sharp bottoms without keelsons in order to support the structure and were reinforced by transverse framing secured with dowels with nails driven through them.
[src:galley/galley-p02] To prevent the hull from hogging there was a **hypozoma** (υπόζωμα = underbelt), a thick, doubled rope that connected bow with stern.
[src:galley/galley-p02] It was kept taut to add strength to the construction along its length, but its exact design or the method of tightening is not known.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The ram, the primary weapon of ancient galleys from around the 8th to the 4th century, was not attached directly on the hull but to a structure extending from it.
[src:galley/galley-p02] This way the ram could twist off if got stuck after ramming rather than breaking the integrity of the hull.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The ram fitting consisted of a massive, projecting timber and the ram itself was a thick bronze casting with horizontal blades that could weigh from 400 kg up to 2 tonnes.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Galleys from 4th century BC up to the time of the early Roman Empire in the 1st century AD became successively larger.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Three levels of oars was the practical upper limit, but it was improved on by making ships longer, broader, and heavier and placing more than one rower per oar.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Naval conflict grew more intense and extensive, and by 100 BC galleys with four, five or six rows of oarsmen were commonplace and carried large complements of soldiers and catapults.
[src:galley/galley-p02] With high freeboard (up to 3 m) and additional tower structures from which missiles could be shot down onto enemy decks, they were intended to be like floating fortresses.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Designs with everything from eight rows of oarsmen and upward were built, but most of them are believed to have been impractical show pieces never used in actual warfare.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Ptolemy IV, the Greek pharaoh of Egypt 221–205 BC, is recorded as building a gigantic ship with *forty* rows of oarsmen, though no specification of its design remains.
[src:galley/galley-p02] One suggested design was that of a huge trireme catamaran with up to 14 men per oar and it is assumed that it was intended as a showpiece rather than a practical warship.
[src:galley/galley-p02] With the consolidation of Roman imperial power, the size of both fleets and galleys decreased considerably.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The huge polyremes disappeared and the fleet were equipped primarily with triremes and liburnians, compact biremes with 25 pairs of oars that were well suited for patrol duty and chasing down raiders and pirates.
[src:galley/galley-p02] In the northern provinces oared patrol boats were employed to keep local tribes in check along the shores of rivers like the Rhine and the Danube.
[src:galley/galley-p02] As the need for large warships disappeared, the design of the trireme, the pinnacle of ancient war ship design, fell into obscurity and was eventually forgotten.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The last known reference to triremes in battle is dated to 324 at the Battle of the Hellespont.
[src:galley/galley-p02] In the late 5th century the Byzantine historian Zosimus declared the knowledge of how to build them to have been long since forgotten.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The primary warship of the Byzantine navy until the 12th century was the dromon and other similar ship types.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Considered an evolution of the Roman liburnian, the term first appeared in the late 5th century, and was commonly used for a specific kind of war-galley by the 6th century.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The term **dromōn** (literally "runner") itself comes from the Greek root **drom-(áō)**, "to run", and 6th-century authors like Procopius are explicit in their references to the speed of these vessels.
[src:galley/galley-p02] During the next few centuries, as the naval struggle with the Arabs intensified, heavier versions with two or possibly even three banks of oars evolved.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The exact reasons for the abandonment of the ram are unclear.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Depictions of upward-pointing beaks in the 4th-century *Vatican Vergil* manuscript may well illustrate that the ram had already been replaced by a spur in late Roman galleys.
[src:galley/galley-p02] One possibility is that the change occurred because of the gradual evolution of the ancient shell-first construction method, against which rams had been designed, into the skeleton-first method, which produced a stronger and more flexible hull, less susceptible to ram attacks.
[src:galley/galley-p02] At least by the early 7th century, the ram's original function had been forgotten.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The dromons that Procopius described were single-banked ships of probably 25 oars per side.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Unlike ancient vessels, which used an outrigger, these extended directly from the hull.
[src:galley/galley-p02] In the later bireme dromons of the 9th and 10th centuries, the two oar banks were divided by the deck, with the first oar bank was situated below, whilst the second oar bank was situated above deck; these rowers were expected to fight alongside the marines in boarding operations.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The overall length of these ships was probably about 32 meters.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The bow spur was intended to ride over an enemy ship's oars, breaking them and rendering it helpless against missile fire and boarding actions.
[src:galley/galley-p02] From the 12th century, the design of war galleys evolved into the form that would remain largely the same until the building of the last war galleys in the late 18th century.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The length to breadth-ratio was a minimum of 8:1.
[src:galley/galley-p02] A rectangular **telaro**, a projecting outrigger, was added to support the oars and the rowers' benches were laid out in a diagonal herringbone pattern angled aft with a central gangway (**corsia**) running along the centerline.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The angling of the benches allowed the rowers to handle individual oars without interfering with each other's movements.
[src:galley/galley-p02] It was based on the form of the **galea**, the smaller Byzantine galleys, and would be known mostly by the Italian term **galea sottile** (literally "slender galley").
[src:galley/galley-p02] A second, smaller mast was added sometime in the 13th century and the number of rowers rose from two to three rowers per bench as a standard from the late 13th to the early 14th century.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The **galee sottili** would make up the bulk the main war fleets of every major naval power in the Mediterranean, assisted by the smaller single-masted **galiotte**, as well as the Christian and Muslim corsairs' fleets.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Ottoman galleys were very similar in design, though in general smaller, faster under sail, but slower under oars.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The standard size of the galley remained stable from the 14th until the early 16th century, when the introduction of naval artillery began to have effects on design and tactics.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The traditional two side rudders were complemented with a stern rudder sometime after c.
[src:galley/galley-p02] 1400 and eventually the side rudders disappeared altogether.
[src:galley/galley-p02] It was also during the 15th century that large artillery pieces were first mounted on galleys.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Burgundian records from the mid-15th century describe galleys with some form of guns, but do not specify the size.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The first conclusive evidence of a large cannon mounted on a galley comes from a woodcut of a Venetian galley in 1486.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The first guns were fixed directly on timbers in the bow and aimed directly forward, a placement that would remain largely unchanged until the galley disappeared from active service in the 19th century.
[src:galley/galley-p02] With the introduction of guns in the bows of galleys, a permanent wooden structure called **rambade** (French: *rambade*; Italian: **rambata**; Spanish: **arrumbada**) was introduced.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The **rambade** became standard on virtually all galleys in the early 16th century.
[src:galley/galley-p02] There were some variations in the navies of different Mediterranean powers, but the overall layout was the same.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The forward-aiming battery was covered by a wooden platform which gave gunners a minimum of protection, and functioned as both a staging area for boarding attacks and as a firing platform for on-board soldiers.
[src:galley/galley-p02] After its introduction, the rambade became a standard detail on every fighting galley until the very end of galley era in the early 19th century.
[src:galley/galley-p02] By the mid-17th century, galleys reached what has been described as their "final form".
[src:galley/galley-p02] Galleys had looked more or less the same for over four centuries and a fairly standardized classification system had been developed by the Mediterranean bureaucracies, based primarily on the number of benches in a vessel.
[src:galley/galley-p02] A Mediterranean galley would have 25 pairs of oars and total of about 500 men.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Command galleys (**lanternas**, "lantern galleys") were even larger with 30 pairs of oars and up to seven rowers per oar.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Armament consisted of one heavy 24- or 36-pounder and two to four 4- to 12-pounders in the bow.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Rows of light swivel guns were often placed along the entire length of the galley on the railings for close-quarter defense.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The length-to-width ratio of the ships was about 8:1, with two masts carrying one large lateen sail each.
[src:galley/galley-p02] In the Baltic, galleys were generally shorter with a length-to-width ratio from 5:1 to 7:1, an adaptation to the cramped conditions of the Baltic archipelagos.
[src:galley/galley-p02] A single mainmast was standard on most war galleys until c.
[src:galley/galley-p02] A second, shorter mast could be raised temporarily in the bows, but became permanent by the early 17th century.
[src:galley/galley-p02] It was stepped slightly to the side to allow for the recoil of the heavy guns; the other was placed roughly in the center of the ship.
[src:galley/galley-p02] A third smaller mast further astern, akin to a mizzen mast, was also introduced on large galleys, possibly in the early 17th century, but was standard at least by the early 18th century.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Galleys had little room for provisions and depended on frequent resupplying and were often beached at night to rest the crew and cook meals.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Where cooking areas were actually present, they consisted of a clay-lined box with a hearth or similar cooking equipment fitted on the vessel in place of a rowing bench, usually on the port (left) side.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Ancient rowing was done in a fixed seated position with rowers facing the stern, the most efficient rowing position.
[src:galley/galley-p02] A sliding stroke, which provided the strength from both legs as well as the arms, was suggested by earlier historians, but no conclusive evidence has supported it.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Practical experiments with the full-scale trireme reconstruction *Olympias* has shown that there was insufficient space to perform a sliding stroke movement, and moving or rolling seats would have been highly impractical to construct with ancient technology.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Rowers in ancient war galleys sat below the upper deck with little view of their surroundings.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The rowing was therefore managed by supervisors, and coordinated with pipes or rhythmic chanting.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Galleys were highly maneuverable, able to turn on their axis or even to row backward, though such maneuvers required a skilled and experienced crew.
[src:galley/galley-p02] In galleys with an arrangement of three men per oar, as in the larger polyremes, all would be seated, but the rower furthest inboard would perform a stand-and-sit stroke, getting up on his feet to push the oar forward, and then sitting down again to pull it back.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The faster a vessel travels, the more energy it uses.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Reaching high speeds requires energy which a human-powered vessel is incapable of producing.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Oar systems generate very low amounts of energy for propulsion (only about 70 W per rower) and the upper limit for rowing in a fixed position is around 18 km/h (11 mph).
[src:galley/galley-p02] Ancient war galleys of the kind used in Classical Greece are by modern historians considered to be the most energy-efficient and fastest of galley designs throughout history.
[src:galley/galley-p02] A full-scale replica of a 5th-century BC trireme, the *Olympias* was built 1985–87 and was put through a series of trials to test its performance.
[src:galley/galley-p02] They proved that a cruising speed of about 14 km/h (9 mph) could be maintained for an entire day of travel.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Sprinting speeds of up to 18 km/h (11 mph) were possible, but only for a few minutes and would tire the crew quickly.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Ancient galleys were lightly built and the original triremes are presumed never to have been surpassed in speed.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Medieval galleys are believed to have been considerably slower, especially since they were not designed for ramming.
[src:galley/galley-p02] A cruising speed of no more than 5 km/h (3 mph) has been estimated.
[src:galley/galley-p02] A sprint speed of up to 13 km/h (8 mph) was possible for 20–30 minutes, but risked exhausting the rowers completely.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Rowing in headwinds or even moderately rough weather was difficult as well as exhausting.
[src:galley/galley-p02] In high seas, ancient galleys would set sail to run before the wind.
[src:galley/galley-p02] They were highly susceptible to high waves, and could become unmanageable if the projecting rowing frame (**apostis**) became overwhelmed by the waves.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Ancient and medieval galleys are assumed to have sailed only with the wind more or less from behind for a top speed of about 15 km/h (9 mph) in fair conditions.
[src:galley/galley-p02] In ancient galleys under sail, most of the motive power came from a single square sail.
[src:galley/galley-p02] It was rigged on a mast somewhat forward of the center of the ship with a smaller mast carrying a head sail in the bow.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Triangular lateen sails are attested as early as the 2nd century AD, and gradually became the sail of choice for galleys.
[src:galley/galley-p02] By the 9th century, lateens were firmly established as part of the standard galley rig.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The lateen rig required a larger crew to handle than a square sail rig, but this was not a problem in the heavily manned galleys.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Unlike a square sail rig, the spar of a lateen sail did not pivot around the mast.
[src:galley/galley-p02] To change tacks, the entire spar had to be raised vertically and passed to the other side of the mast.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Since a lateen spar was longer than the mast itself, and not much shorter than the ship itself, this was more complex and potentially dangerous compared to tacking with a square rig.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Contrary to the popular image of rowers chained to the oars, conveyed by movies such as *Ben Hur*, there is no evidence that ancient navies made regular use of condemned criminals or slaves as oarsmen, with the possible exception of Ptolemaic Egypt.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Literary evidence indicates that both Greek and Roman navies relied on paid labor or ordinary soldiers to man their galleys.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Slaves were put at the oars only in times of crisis.
[src:galley/galley-p02] In some cases, these people would be given freedom after the crisis was averted.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Roman merchant vessels (usually sailing vessels) were manned by slaves, sometimes even with slaves as ship's master, but this was seldom the case in merchant galleys.
[src:galley/galley-p02] It was only in the early 16th century that galley slaves became commonplace.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Both galley fleets and the size of individual vessels increased in size during the early modern period, which required more rowers.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The number of benches could not be increased without lengthening hulls beyond their structural limits, and more than three oars per bench was not practicable.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The demand for more rowers also meant that the relatively limited number of skilled oarsmen could not keep up with the demand of the larger fleets.
[src:galley/galley-p02] It became increasingly common to man galleys with convicts or slaves, which required a simpler method of rowing.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The older method of employing professional rowers using the **alla sensile** method (one oar per rower, with two to three rower sharing the same bench) was gradually phased out in favor of **a scaloccio**, which required less skill.
[src:galley/galley-p02] A single large oar was used for each bench, with several rowers working the oar together.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The number of oarsmen per oar rose from three up to five and in some of the largest command galleys, there could be as many as seven to an oar.
[src:galley/galley-p02] All major Mediterranean powers sentenced criminals to galley service, but initially only in time of war.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Christian naval powers such as Spain frequently employed Muslim captives and prisoners of war.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The Ottoman navy and its North African corsair allies put Christian prisoners to the oars in large numbers, but also mixed with volunteers.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Habsburg Spain relied mostly on servile rowers, in great part because its organizational structure was geared toward employing slaves and convicts.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Venice was one of few major Mediterranean powers that used almost only free rowers, a result of their reliance on *alla sensile* rowing which required skilled professional rowers.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The Knights of Saint John used slaves extensively, as did the Papal States, Florence, and Genoa.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The North African ghazi corsairs relied almost entirely on Christian slaves as rowers.
[src:galley/galley-p02] In the earliest times of naval warfare, boarding was the only means of deciding a naval engagement, but little to nothing is known about the tactics involved.
[src:galley/galley-p02] In the first recorded naval battle, the Battle of the Delta, the battle was fought in close combat melee with the support of archers, some perched on raised platforms.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The Egyptian victory was commemorated on the mortuary temple of Ramesses III at Medinet Habu and shows intense close quarters fighting and the use of grapnels thrown into the rigging to capsize ships and throwing its crew into the sea.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Around the 8th century BC, ramming began to be employed as war galleys were equipped with heavy bronze rams.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Records of the Persian Wars in the early 5th century BC by the Ancient historian Herodotus (c.
[src:galley/galley-p02] 484–25 BC) show that by this time ramming tactics had evolved among the Greeks.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Ramming itself was done by smashing into the rear or side of an enemy ship, punching a hole in the planking.
[src:galley/galley-p02] This would not actually sink an ancient galley unless it was heavily laden with cargo and stores.
[src:galley/galley-p02] With a normal load, it was buoyant enough to float even with a breached hull.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Breaking the enemy's oars was another way of rendering ships immobile, rendering them easier targets.
[src:galley/galley-p02] If ramming was not possible or successful, the on-board complement of soldiers would attempt to board and capture the enemy vessel by securing it with grappling irons, accompanied by missile fire with arrows or javelins.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Trying to set the enemy ship on fire by hurling incendiary missiles or by pouring the content of fire pots attached to long handles is thought to have been used, especially since smoke below decks would easily disable rowers.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Ramming tactics were gradually superseded in the last centuries BC by the Macedonians and Romans, both primarily land-based powers.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Hand-to-hand fighting with large complements of heavy infantry supported by ship-borne catapults dominated the fighting style during the Roman era.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Thought this decreased mobility of vessels, it meant that less skill was required from individual oarsmen.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Fleets thereby became less dependent on highly skilled rowers with a lifetime of experience at the oar.
[src:galley/galley-p02] By the first centuries AD, ramming tactics had completely disappeared along with the knowledge of the design of the ancient trireme.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Medieval galleys instead developed a projection, or "spur", in the bow that was designed to break oars and act as a boarding platform for taking enemy ships.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The only remaining examples of ramming tactics were occasional attempts to collide with enemy ships in order to destabilize or capsize them.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The Byzantine navy, the largest Mediterranean war fleet throughout most of the Early Middle Ages, employed crescent formations in order to turn the enemy's flanks, as did the Arab fleets that fought them from the 7th century onward.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The initial stages in naval battles was an exchanges of missiles, ranging from combustible projectiles to arrows, caltrops, and javelins.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The aim was not to sink ships, but to deplete the ranks of enemy crews before boarding, which decided the outcome.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Byzantine dromons had pavesades (racks of large shields along the railings) which provided protection to the deck crew.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Larger ships also had wooden castles between the masts on either side of the upper decks, which allowed archers to shoot from an elevated firing position.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Later medieval navies continued to use similar tactics, with a line abreast formation as standard, as galleys were intended to be fought from the bow.
[src:galley/galley-p02] They were at their weakest along the sides, especially in the middle.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The crescent formation employed by the Byzantines continued to be used throughout the Middle Ages.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The ships on the edges of the crescent would attempt to crash their bows straight into the sides of the enemy ships at the edge of the formation.
[src:galley/galley-p02] In large-scale galley-to-galley engagements, tactics remained essentially the same until the end of the 16th century, even with the introduction of heavy guns.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Since galleys could close the reliable maximum range of early naval guns faster than the guns could be reloaded, gun crews would hold their fire until the last possible moment.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Shortly before impact, all available guns would fire, similar to infantry tactics in the era of short-range, inaccurate firearms.
[src:galley/galley-p02] In extreme cases, such last-second discharges could kill dozens of men instantly, dealing a severe shock to the enemy.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Unless one side could outmaneuver the other, lines of galleys would crash into each other head on.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Individual ships would then be locked bow to bow in close formation and each ship would be fought over in close-quarters combat.
[src:galley/galley-p02] As long as a vessel was not completely overrun, reinforcements could be fed into the fight from reserve vessels in the rear.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The earliest guns were of large calibers, initially of wrought iron, which made them weak compared to the cast bronze guns that would become standard in the 16th century.
[src:galley/galley-p02] Early on, guns would be fixed directly to the bow timbers, aimed directly forward in the direction of travel.
[src:galley/galley-p02] This placement would remain essentially the same until the galley disappeared from active service in the early 19th century.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The introduction of heavy guns and handheld firearms did not change tactics considerably.
[src:galley/galley-p02] If anything, it made the bow even more important in offense, both as a staging area for boarders and the obvious place for concentrating firepower.
[src:galley/galley-p02] The galley itself could easily outperform most sailing vessels before the establishment of the full-rigged ship.
[src:galley/galley-p02] It retained a distinct tactical advantage even after the initial introduction of naval artillery because of the ease with which it could be maneuvered to bare its guns upon an opposing vessel.
[src:galley/galley-p03] Galleys were frequently used for ceremonial purposes.
[src:galley/galley-p03] In early modern Europe, galleys enjoyed a level of prestige that sailing vessels could not compete with.
[src:galley/galley-p03] They were considered to be more closely associated with warfare on land, and fought with similar tactics.
[src:galley/galley-p03] Naval warfare did not have the same association with chivalry and martial prowess as land warfare, which was seen as the ultimate achievement of nobility and royalty.
[src:galley/galley-p03] In the Baltic, Gustav I, the first king of the modern Swedish state, showed particular interest in galleys, as was befitting a Renaissance prince.
[src:galley/galley-p03] Whenever traveling by sea, Gustav, his court, royal bureaucrats, and his bodyguard would travel by galley.
[src:galley/galley-p03] Around the same time, English king Henry VIII had Mediterranean-style galleys built and even manned them with slaves, though the English navy of the time relied mostly on sailing ships.
[src:galley/galley-p03] British naval historian Nicholas Rodger has described the galley as a "supreme symbol of royal power ... derived from its intimate association with armies, and consequently with princes".
[src:galley/galley-p03] This association was elevated even further by the French "Sun King", Louis XIV, in the form of a dedicated galley corps.
[src:galley/galley-p03] Louis and the French state he ruled created a tool and symbol of royal authority that did little fighting, but was a potent extension of absolutist ambitions.
[src:galley/galley-p03] Galleys were built to scale for the royal flotilla on the Grand Canal at the Gardens of Versailles, purely for the amusement of the court.
[src:galley/galley-p03] French royal galleys patrolled the Mediterranean, forcing ships of other states to salute the King's banner, convoyed ambassadors and cardinals, and participated obediently in naval parades and royal pageantry.
[src:galley/galley-p03] Historian Paul Bamford has described galleys as vessels that "must have appealed to military men and to aristocratic officers ... accustomed to being obeyed and served".
[src:galley/galley-p03] Sentencing criminals, political dissenters and religious deviants to the galleys also turned the French galley corps into a brutal, cost-effective and feared prison system.
[src:galley/galley-p03] French Protestants were particularly ill-treated in this system.
[src:galley/galley-p03] They were only a small minority of the prisoners, but their experiences came to dominate the legacy of the galley corps.
[src:galley/galley-p03] In 1909, French author Albert Savine (1859–1927) wrote that "[a]fter the Bastille, the galleys were the greatest horror of the old regime".
[src:galley/galley-p03] Long after convicts stopped serving in the galleys, even after the reign of Napoleon, the term *galérien* ("galley rower") remained a general term for forced labor and convicts serving harsh sentences.
